1
00:00:15,314 --> 00:00:18,280
[ Applause ]

2
00:00:18,347 --> 00:00:21,608
##

3
00:00:21,680 --> 00:00:25,510
Toot-Toot-Tootsie good-bye

4
00:00:25,579 --> 00:00:29,068
Toot-Toot-Tootsie don't cry

5
00:00:29,314 --> 00:00:32,905
The little choo-choo train
that takes me

6
00:00:32,980 --> 00:00:36,469
Away from you, You don't know
just how sad it makes me

7
00:00:36,513 --> 00:00:40,378
Kiss me Tootsie and then

8
00:00:40,447 --> 00:00:43,640
Do it over again

9
00:00:43,713 --> 00:00:47,441
Watch for the mail I'll never fail

10
00:00:47,513 --> 00:00:51,502
If you don't get a letter then
you know I'm in jail Hey, hey

11
00:00:51,579 --> 00:00:54,670
Don't cry, Tootsie Don't cry

12
00:00:54,746 --> 00:00:58,270
Kiss me, Tootsie Good-bye

13
00:00:58,347 --> 00:01:02,006
#[ Whistling ]

14
00:01:34,280 --> 00:01:37,405
Get hot Don't cry, Tootsie Don't cry

15
00:01:38,680 --> 00:01:43,738
Good-bye, Tootsie Oh, good-bye#

16
00:01:43,813 --> 00:01:46,506
I'm an artist, and I won't change
a word of my play...

17
00:01:46,579 --> 00:01:48,636
to pander to some commercial
Broadway audience!

18
00:01:48,713 --> 00:01:51,804
I'm not arguing with you!
Do you see me arguing?

19
00:01:51,880 --> 00:01:55,505
Your play is great as is. It's real.
It makes a point. It's confrontational.

20
00:01:55,579 --> 00:01:59,034
- Then why won't you produce it?
- Because I cannot afford
another failure.

21
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:02,371
- David, the play's too heavy.
- But not everybody writes to distract.

22
00:02:02,447 --> 00:02:05,277
- [ Groans ]
- It's the theater's duty
not just to entertain...

23
00:02:05,347 --> 00:02:07,835
- but to transform men's souls.
- Oh, come on.

24
00:02:07,913 --> 00:02:11,311
You're not at one of your sidewalk cafes
in Greenwich Village. This is Broadway.

25
00:02:11,380 --> 00:02:14,073
- You said you believed in my play!
- What do you want me to say?

26
00:02:14,314 --> 00:02:17,575
I'm tapped out. Maybe if we got some
big-time director interested...

27
00:02:17,646 --> 00:02:20,840
- I could scare up backers--
- No, no, no. I'm directing this play.

28
00:02:20,913 --> 00:02:23,970
Ohh, will you listen to this guy?
Where's your track record?

29
00:02:24,047 --> 00:02:26,740
I won't see my work mangled again.
I've been through this twice before.

30
00:02:26,813 --> 00:02:29,745
Two powerful scripts,
could have been tremendous successes...

31
00:02:29,813 --> 00:02:34,337
and I had to watch actors change
my dialogue and directors
misinterpret everything!

32
00:02:34,414 --> 00:02:36,346
I know. I know.
You're an artist.

33
00:02:36,414 --> 00:02:41,346
Let me tell you, kid, that's the
real world out there, and it's
a lot rougher than you think.

34
00:02:42,713 --> 00:02:46,543
Ma
He's makin' eyes at me

35
00:02:46,613 --> 00:02:50,511
Ma
He's awful nice to me

36
00:02:50,579 --> 00:02:55,308
Ma, he's almost
breakin' my heart

37
00:02:55,347 --> 00:02:58,642
What are you waitin' for?
Kill them!

38
00:03:00,646 --> 00:03:02,771
Come on. Let's go
get somethin' to eat.

39
00:03:02,846 --> 00:03:05,778
- I feel like eatin' ribs.
- That's a good idea.

40
00:03:05,846 --> 00:03:10,370
I gotta go shoot crap at Tommy's. He's
got a game at the Ansonia. I gotta go.

41
00:03:10,447 --> 00:03:14,038
Somebody's got to let
Mr. Valenti know what's going on.
He's at the Three Deuces.

42
00:03:14,280 --> 00:03:17,803
- Why don't you go tell him?
- I promised Bobby Doyle.
I can't do nothin'.

43
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:22,835
- I gotta shoot a game.
- What's a matter, Cheech? Don't
you wanna baby-sit his girl?

44
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:24,971
His girlfriend's
a pain in my ass.

45
00:03:25,047 --> 00:03:28,945
You gotta see Mama
every night

46
00:03:29,013 --> 00:03:32,446
Or you can't see Mama
at all

47
00:03:32,513 --> 00:03:36,310
You gotta kiss Mama
Treat her right

48
00:03:36,380 --> 00:03:39,971
Or she won't be home
when you call

49
00:03:40,047 --> 00:03:43,570
Now if you want
my company

50
00:03:43,646 --> 00:03:46,544
- Here, doll, take care of this hat.
- You can't fifty-fifty me

51
00:03:46,613 --> 00:03:49,807
- Mr. V. here?
- Yeah, right this way.

52
00:03:49,880 --> 00:03:53,835
-Nice crowd.
-Yeah, we're packin' 'em in every night.

53
00:03:53,913 --> 00:03:58,073
- Right here.
- Monday night I sat alone

54
00:03:58,314 --> 00:04:02,007
Tuesday night
you didn't phone

55
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:06,274
Wednesday night
you didn't call

56
00:04:06,347 --> 00:04:10,439
- Done.
- Now that's a load
off my mind. How many?

57
00:04:10,513 --> 00:04:13,946
- Four.
- This means we ain't heard the last.

58
00:04:14,013 --> 00:04:17,638
You know Kustabeck's gonna have a fit,
but he'll run scared.

59
00:04:17,680 --> 00:04:20,476
- Maybe.
- Listen, a deal's a deal.

60
00:04:20,546 --> 00:04:25,843
- We got midtown. I mean, eh...
Mr. Valenti does.
- [ Whistling ]

61
00:04:25,913 --> 00:04:28,708
I don't want that kind
of a sheik

62
00:04:28,780 --> 00:04:31,372
Who does his sheiking
once a week

63
00:04:31,447 --> 00:04:36,538
You gotta see Mama
every night

64
00:04:36,613 --> 00:04:39,545
Or you can't see

65
00:04:39,613 --> 00:04:47,445
You can't see Mama
at all

66
00:04:48,314 --> 00:04:50,609
Not at all.

67
00:04:50,680 --> 00:04:53,374
[ Applause ]

68
00:04:53,447 --> 00:04:56,503
I'm fed up!
I'm fed up, do you hear me?

69
00:04:56,579 --> 00:05:00,773
You can push your torpedoes around all
you want, but I've had it up to here!

70
00:05:00,846 --> 00:05:03,641
- What is it now?
- I am not sharing a dressing room.

71
00:05:03,680 --> 00:05:08,510
I am tired of getting
bumped into and stepped on.
None of these bimbos knows how to dance.

72
00:05:08,546 --> 00:05:11,308
- Bimbos!
- They're the best line in New York.

73
00:05:11,380 --> 00:05:13,504
- Bullshit! Bullshit!
- Oh, knock it off.

74
00:05:13,579 --> 00:05:16,045
- Hey, clam up over there.
Olive, come on.
- What?

75
00:05:16,280 --> 00:05:19,269
- Olive, it's our anniversary.
- It's not our anniversary.

76
00:05:19,347 --> 00:05:21,778
-You're getting senile.
-It's September 28. Six months to today.

77
00:05:21,846 --> 00:05:23,778
- So?
- I remember it like it was yesterday...

78
00:05:23,846 --> 00:05:26,539
'cause that's the morning
we broke Joey Benjamin's legs.

79
00:05:26,613 --> 00:05:29,307
- Six months? Six months!
- Yeah. Six months.

80
00:05:29,347 --> 00:05:33,439
- And I'm still stuck
in this crummy rat trap!
- Olive. I brought you somethin'.

81
00:05:33,513 --> 00:05:35,309
- What is it?
- Open it.

82
00:05:35,347 --> 00:05:39,540
- No, you open it.
Can't you see I'm dressing?
- I'll open it. Here. Hey.

83
00:05:39,613 --> 00:05:42,545
- What is it?
- Pearls! What the hell
do you think they are?

84
00:05:42,579 --> 00:05:44,704
- Pearls are white.
- These are black pearls.

85
00:05:44,780 --> 00:05:48,576
Don't give me that!
I never heard of black pearls.

86
00:05:48,646 --> 00:05:51,272
Just 'cause you never heard of somethin'
don't mean it don't exist.

87
00:05:51,347 --> 00:05:55,279
What do you think I am? Some kind
of chump? They're black, for God's sake.

88
00:05:55,347 --> 00:05:59,836
- They probably came
from defective oysters.
- The pearls ain't sick.

89
00:05:59,913 --> 00:06:03,606
Black pearls, they're supposed--
What? They're supposed to be black!

90
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:07,374
- Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.
- Don't be that way.
You know I'm nuts about you.

91
00:06:07,447 --> 00:06:11,811
If you're nuts about me, Nickie,
why don't you get me out
of this lousy chorus line?

92
00:06:11,880 --> 00:06:15,472
I came to New York to be an actress.
That's where my gifts are.

93
00:06:15,546 --> 00:06:19,377
You will, baby. You'll be a great
actress. A promise is a promise.

94
00:06:19,447 --> 00:06:23,640
- Yeah, I--
- Come on. Get yourself dressed.
I'm takin' you to Harlem.

95
00:06:23,713 --> 00:06:27,305
- The Cotton Club?
- Yeah, baby. [ Chuckles ]

96
00:06:27,380 --> 00:06:30,573
[ David ] I'm telling you,
they read my play, they love it.
But they're afraid of it.

97
00:06:30,646 --> 00:06:32,908
- [ Man ] It's irrelevant.
- It's not irrelevant!

98
00:06:32,980 --> 00:06:35,912
The point
I'm making is that...

99
00:06:35,980 --> 00:06:40,503
no truly great artist has ever
been appreciated in his lifetime.

100
00:06:40,579 --> 00:06:42,545
- Not one?
- No, no.

101
00:06:42,579 --> 00:06:47,841
- Flender.
- Take, uh, uh... Van Gogh
or Edgar Allen Poe.

102
00:06:47,913 --> 00:06:51,811
Poe died poor and freezing
with his cat curled on his feet.

103
00:06:51,880 --> 00:06:55,438
David, don't give up on it.
Maybe it'll be produced posthumously.

104
00:06:55,513 --> 00:06:59,469
You know, I-I-I have never
had a play produced-- That's right.

105
00:06:59,546 --> 00:07:03,638
- And I've written one play every
year for the past 20 years.
- That's because you're a genius.

106
00:07:03,713 --> 00:07:07,476
The proof is that both common
people and intellectuals find
your work completely incoherent.

107
00:07:07,546 --> 00:07:10,842
- It means you're a genius.
- We all have our moments of doubt.

108
00:07:10,913 --> 00:07:16,812
I paint a canvas every week, take one
look at it and slash it with a razor.

109
00:07:16,846 --> 00:07:20,676
- Well, in your case that's a good idea.
- I have faith in your plays.

110
00:07:20,713 --> 00:07:24,509
- She has faith in my plays
because she loves me.
- Also because you're a genius.

111
00:07:24,579 --> 00:07:27,511
Ten years ago, I-I-I kidnapped
this woman from a very beautiful...

112
00:07:27,579 --> 00:07:30,841
middle-class life in Pittsburgh, and
I made her life miserable ever since.

113
00:07:30,913 --> 00:07:33,902
Hey, Ellen, as long
as he's a good man, keep him.

114
00:07:33,980 --> 00:07:37,844
You know, I think the mistake
we women make is we fall
in love with the artist--

115
00:07:37,880 --> 00:07:39,846
- Hey, you guys, are you listening?
- Yes, yes.

116
00:07:39,880 --> 00:07:42,539
- We fall in love with
the artist, not the man.
- I don't think that's a mistake.

117
00:07:42,613 --> 00:07:45,045
- How is that a mistake?
- [ Woman ] The artist makes the man.

118
00:07:45,280 --> 00:07:49,303
She's right. You can't
separate 'em. No, look. Say
there was a burning building...

119
00:07:49,380 --> 00:07:52,675
and you could rush in, and
you could save only one thing:

120
00:07:52,713 --> 00:07:57,805
either the last known copy
of Shakespeare's plays or
some anonymous human being.

121
00:07:57,846 --> 00:07:59,903
- You cannot--
- What would you do?

122
00:07:59,980 --> 00:08:02,469
- You cannot deprive the world
of those plays.
- Correct.

123
00:08:02,546 --> 00:08:04,944
- Phone call, David.
- [ Girl ] It's an inanimate object.

124
00:08:05,013 --> 00:08:09,775
It's not an inanimate object!
It's art! Art is life! It lives!

125
00:08:09,846 --> 00:08:12,778
We got the money.
We can do the play.

126
00:08:12,813 --> 00:08:15,506
What? When? How?

127
00:08:15,579 --> 00:08:18,545
A single backer
goin' for the whole show.

128
00:08:18,613 --> 00:08:21,807
An old acquaintance. I'm up
at the Cotton Club. I ran into him.

129
00:08:21,880 --> 00:08:25,313
- And no hitches?
- Well, uh--

130
00:08:25,347 --> 00:08:29,574
We'll meet tomorrow and discuss it,
all right? Luxor Baths. Noon.

131
00:08:31,414 --> 00:08:35,778
Are you nuts? You think I'm gonna let
some amateur play the lead in my play?

132
00:08:35,846 --> 00:08:38,472
Did I say "lead"?
Did I say "lead," Mr. Genius?

133
00:08:38,513 --> 00:08:41,638
- Some guy's girlfriend 'cause
he's puttin' up the money?
- Did I say "lead"?

134
00:08:41,713 --> 00:08:44,645
I said a part, a role.
I thought maybe Dr. Philips.

135
00:08:44,680 --> 00:08:47,805
- The psychiatrist? It's a key role.
- What key role?

136
00:08:47,846 --> 00:08:51,006
- It's a small part. Key role!
- Who is this woman anyway?

137
00:08:51,080 --> 00:08:54,705
Olive Neal? I don't even know what
she looks like, much less can she act.

138
00:08:54,780 --> 00:08:57,746
He says she's the stuff
that stars are made of.

139
00:08:57,813 --> 00:09:00,711
That's 'cause he's in love with her.
And who is he anyway?

140
00:09:00,780 --> 00:09:05,270
- His name is Nick Valenti.
- How-How-- How do I know
that name? What's he do?

141
00:09:05,347 --> 00:09:08,710
- Ah, he's got his finger
in a number of pies.
- I don't like the sound of this.

142
00:09:08,780 --> 00:09:11,837
- Look, you wanna
get your play on or not?
- I gotta meet her first.

143
00:09:11,913 --> 00:09:14,004
- So you'll meet her.
- I'm conflicted.

144
00:09:14,080 --> 00:09:17,807
-You'll meet her. That's all I'm saying.
-The psychiatrist is not small.

145
00:09:17,846 --> 00:09:22,801
It's not the lead. It's-- It's a
small part. Who do you see in the lead?

146
00:09:22,846 --> 00:09:25,676
- I don't know.
- What about Helen Sinclair?

147
00:09:25,746 --> 00:09:29,644
Oh, sure. I mean, she'd be great.
But can we get her?

148
00:09:29,713 --> 00:09:32,475
Why can't we get her? She's been in
nothin' but flops the past three years.

149
00:09:32,546 --> 00:09:34,479
Yeah, but she's
a major actress.

150
00:09:34,513 --> 00:09:36,672
[ Chuckles ]
Was.

151
00:09:36,746 --> 00:09:39,610
She'd be great.
I mean, really, she's brilliant.

152
00:09:39,680 --> 00:09:42,942
- She possess the necessary fire.
For the part, she'd be great.
- You really think so?

153
00:09:43,013 --> 00:09:45,706
- I'm glad you think so.
- Think we can get her?

154
00:09:45,780 --> 00:09:49,678
- I sent the script
to her agent, Sidney Loomis.
- You did?

155
00:09:49,746 --> 00:09:53,372
- Did I do wrong? Did I do wrong?
- No, no.

156
00:09:53,447 --> 00:09:56,072
- Did I do wrong not checking
with you first?
- Not at all.

157
00:09:56,314 --> 00:09:59,007
- If so, I stand corrected. I mean that.
- No, really.

158
00:09:59,047 --> 00:10:02,740
- Helen Sinclair... really.
- Get it out.

159
00:10:02,813 --> 00:10:06,371
- She's great.
- Well, all we can do
is hope for the best.

160
00:10:06,447 --> 00:10:09,537
You must be joking!

161
00:10:09,613 --> 00:10:14,602
You want me to play some frumpy
housewife who gets dumped for a flapper?

162
00:10:14,680 --> 00:10:18,806
Don't you remember who I am?
Don't you know who you represent?

163
00:10:18,846 --> 00:10:22,835
- I'm Helen Sinclair!
- Definitely! You are
definitely Helen Sinclair.

164
00:10:22,913 --> 00:10:27,572
I look at you and I say Helen Sinclair!
But who better to play that role?

165
00:10:27,646 --> 00:10:30,408
- Under whose direction? Some novice!
- He's the author.

166
00:10:30,480 --> 00:10:34,071
- Of two flops.
- Julian says it was the directors
that messed up those projects.

167
00:10:34,314 --> 00:10:39,837
Julian Marx! I do plays put on
by Belasco or Sam Harris.

168
00:10:39,913 --> 00:10:43,346
Not some Yiddish pants salesman
turned producer.

169
00:10:43,414 --> 00:10:47,675
My ex-husband used to say,
"lf you're gonna go down,
go down with the best of them."

170
00:10:47,746 --> 00:10:51,440
- Which ex-husband?
- Oh, I don't know which ex-husband.
The one with the moustache.

171
00:10:51,513 --> 00:10:54,809
Listen to me. Authors are very often
the best directors of their own works.

172
00:10:54,880 --> 00:10:58,005
She's dowdy! Sid, the ingenue
has all the hot lines.

173
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:00,671
Even the female psychiatrist
is a better role.

174
00:11:00,746 --> 00:11:03,712
But the role of Sylvia Poston
is the lead.

175
00:11:03,780 --> 00:11:08,644
Sylvia Poston.
Even the name reeks of Orbach's!

176
00:11:08,680 --> 00:11:12,374
I do Electra!
I do Lady Macbeth!

177
00:11:12,447 --> 00:11:17,708
I do plays by Noel and Phil Barry
or at least Max Anderson.

178
00:11:17,780 --> 00:11:22,406
Helen, listen to me. This is
a major part in a serious play.

179
00:11:22,480 --> 00:11:25,968
And let's face it, Helen. You have
not been in a hit in a long time.

180
00:11:26,013 --> 00:11:30,036
- In a long, long, long time.
- I'm still a star!

181
00:11:31,480 --> 00:11:34,412
I never play
frumps or virgins.

182
00:11:34,480 --> 00:11:36,843
You're a star because you're great,
and you are a great star.

183
00:11:36,880 --> 00:11:38,846
- But let me tell you somethin'.
- [ Bell Rings ]

184
00:11:38,880 --> 00:11:40,846
In the last couple of years...

185
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:43,573
you're better known as an adulteress and
a drunk-- I say this in all due respect.

186
00:11:43,646 --> 00:11:46,010
I haven't had a drink
since New Year's Eve.

187
00:11:46,047 --> 00:11:48,013
- We're talkin' Chinese New Year's.
- Naturally.

188
00:11:48,047 --> 00:11:50,638
Still, that's two days, Sid.
You know how long that is for me?

189
00:11:50,713 --> 00:11:53,271
- What is it, Josette?
- [ Woman ] Some flowers.

190
00:11:53,347 --> 00:11:55,313
Well, bring them here,
will you?

191
00:11:55,347 --> 00:11:58,540
The offers are not pourin' in
like they used to.

192
00:11:58,613 --> 00:12:01,045
They're from David Shayne.

193
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:04,905
"As a small artist to a greater one.
That you merely consider my play...

194
00:12:04,980 --> 00:12:08,469
is all the fulfillment
I require.

195
00:12:08,513 --> 00:12:10,480
Hmm.

196
00:12:12,380 --> 00:12:17,312
- What's he like?
- I hear he's terrific.
A genius ready to emerge.

197
00:12:17,380 --> 00:12:20,641
- I have to be billed over the title.
- Where else?

198
00:12:20,713 --> 00:12:25,271
- Approval of the leading man.
The star's dressing room.
- This is not even a question.

199
00:12:25,347 --> 00:12:27,744
Approval of
all photos of me.

200
00:12:27,813 --> 00:12:30,336
Oh, it's still not
a very glamorous role.

201
00:12:30,380 --> 00:12:34,278
But maybe I could meet with David.
Maybe we could go over the script.

202
00:12:34,347 --> 00:12:38,302
Maybe there's a few ways
we could find to brighten her up. Hmm?

203
00:12:38,347 --> 00:12:40,438
Why am I nervous?

204
00:12:41,713 --> 00:12:45,645
- That was sad. Clara Bow had it rough.
- She's a doll.

205
00:12:45,680 --> 00:12:49,635
- I'd do anything to be in a movie.
- You're pretty enough.

206
00:12:49,713 --> 00:12:53,077
Do you think you could
ever speak to Mr. Valenti?

207
00:12:53,314 --> 00:12:55,871
- Mr. Valenti knows everybody.
He'll do the right thing.
- That's right.

208
00:12:55,946 --> 00:12:59,537
I hear he's gonna make Olive Neal
a Broadway star. [ Screams ]

209
00:12:59,613 --> 00:13:03,444
[ Gunshots ]

210
00:13:06,813 --> 00:13:09,473
Go, go, go!

211
00:13:09,546 --> 00:13:11,910
Where'd it happen?

212
00:13:11,980 --> 00:13:15,469
Who'd they get?
Oh, Jesus!

213
00:13:15,513 --> 00:13:18,707
All right, I'm gonna be
at Olive's for about an hour.

214
00:13:18,780 --> 00:13:22,008
You get some more guys downstairs
and call me back on the Masucci thing.

215
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:25,274
-This is for Leo Kustabeck, you hear me?
-[ Olive ] Hey!

216
00:13:25,347 --> 00:13:29,279
- You said this was the lead.
It's a smaller part.
- All right.

217
00:13:29,347 --> 00:13:31,972
- I got no time now.
- It's a smaller part.
I don't believe it.

218
00:13:32,047 --> 00:13:34,979
- They just got Vinny and Sal
outside a movie house.
- I counted the lines.

219
00:13:35,013 --> 00:13:38,877
- Sylvia Poston is the lead.
I'm just backing her up.
- You hear what I said?

220
00:13:38,946 --> 00:13:43,470
- I'm tired of backing people up.
I wanna be the lead.
- Julian says you're a doctor.

221
00:13:43,513 --> 00:13:47,310
- A doctor. I don't wanna be
a doctor. I wanna be the lead.
- A head doctor. It's a big part.

222
00:13:47,347 --> 00:13:50,006
A head doctor,
but it ain't the lead.

223
00:13:50,047 --> 00:13:52,706
- So don't try and snow me.
- You'd squawk if they
hung you with a new rope.

224
00:13:52,780 --> 00:13:55,769
- I know a lead when I see a lead,
and this ain't the lead.
- [ Phone Ringing ]

225
00:13:55,846 --> 00:13:59,472
- A lead is on every single page.
A lead has lots of scenes.
- Hello? Oh, Vito.

226
00:13:59,546 --> 00:14:04,343
- Ya heard? Get everybody
together at the garage.
- I don't get to kiss nobody.

227
00:14:04,414 --> 00:14:07,346
- No, I want it done today!
What is it with you?
- Hey!

228
00:14:07,414 --> 00:14:11,573
- You wanna take your business
outta here? We got guests!
- Call me back.

229
00:14:11,646 --> 00:14:14,806
- I got trouble here.
- I don't care about your trouble.

230
00:14:14,880 --> 00:14:17,472
- What am I supposed to do?
Just foot the bills around here?
- I don't care.

231
00:14:17,546 --> 00:14:22,672
- And I want my say with
this Broadway big shot too.
- Okay, just don't embarrass me.

232
00:14:22,746 --> 00:14:26,338
- I'm lookin' out
for your interests, okay?
- [ Woman ] Miss Olive?

233
00:14:26,414 --> 00:14:30,675
- There's a Mr. Marx and--
- I know, I know. Send 'em in, Venus.

234
00:14:30,746 --> 00:14:32,974
- Listen. When they get here...
- What?

235
00:14:33,047 --> 00:14:36,343
- charm 'em a little, baby.
- You're the one that
needs charm lessons.

236
00:14:36,414 --> 00:14:39,607
- I told them you're a great actress.
- I am a great actress.

237
00:14:39,680 --> 00:14:42,771
Nick Valenti!
Say hello to David Shayne.

238
00:14:42,813 --> 00:14:45,371
- [ Valenti ] David, how are you?
- Hello. I'm Olive.

239
00:14:45,447 --> 00:14:47,470
- This is Olive Neal.
- Charmed, charmed, charmed.

240
00:14:47,513 --> 00:14:50,536
- Come on in. Come on.
- Come on in.

241
00:14:50,613 --> 00:14:53,579
- Hey, Dave, she read your play.
She thinks it's great.
- Yes, I read your play.

242
00:14:53,646 --> 00:14:56,442
It's thrilling, turbulent,
a page turner.

243
00:14:56,513 --> 00:14:59,071
Charmed, charmed,
charmed, charmed.

244
00:14:59,314 --> 00:15:01,575
She's a great little actress.
Just needs a break.

245
00:15:01,646 --> 00:15:04,578
- What have you been in, Miss, uh--
- Olive. Olive. Olive.

246
00:15:04,646 --> 00:15:06,669
- Call me Olive, honey.
- You smoke?
- No.

247
00:15:06,746 --> 00:15:09,474
- Olive, ah, your--
well, your experience?
- I love the play.

248
00:15:09,513 --> 00:15:11,945
- Well, I, uh--
- Oh, she ain't got no experience.

249
00:15:12,013 --> 00:15:14,411
- I do too. I have too.
- She's a natural.

250
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:16,502
- I have experience.
- They ain't talkin' dancin', Olive.

251
00:15:16,579 --> 00:15:19,977
- He doesn't know
what he's talkin' about.
- You don't mean dancin', do you?

252
00:15:20,047 --> 00:15:24,741
She used to wiggle at this joint
in Hoboken. Pick up quarters
off the tabletops with her--

253
00:15:24,813 --> 00:15:28,041
- Hey! Butt out, why don't ya!
They're talkin' to me!
- I'm tryin' to break the ice.

254
00:15:28,280 --> 00:15:31,303
- Who wants a drink?
- I'll have a double anything. Be great.

255
00:15:31,380 --> 00:15:33,607
- [ Marx ] No, I have an ulcer.
- Venus, a double whiskey.

256
00:15:33,680 --> 00:15:37,306
- Make it two, Venus.
- Do you want the blue
stuff or the green?

257
00:15:37,380 --> 00:15:40,937
- The imported, dummy.
- Oh, you mean from the clean bathtub.

258
00:15:41,013 --> 00:15:42,774
Mm-hmm.

259
00:15:44,347 --> 00:15:48,370
- So you never acted before?
- Honey, honey. Yes, I have acted.

260
00:15:48,447 --> 00:15:53,038
I have acted. I've acted a lot.
I was in a musical revue.
Can you light this for me?

261
00:15:53,280 --> 00:15:56,837
Geez. No manners.
No gentleman.

262
00:15:58,280 --> 00:16:00,939
Yeah, I did a musical revue
in Wichita.

263
00:16:01,013 --> 00:16:04,809
Maybe you heard of it. It was called
Leave A Specimen. I had two songs.

264
00:16:04,880 --> 00:16:08,005
- [ Phone Ringing ]
- Two numbers. Two thrilling,
show-stopping numbers.

265
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:10,841
I'm actually feeling
a little sick, really.

266
00:16:10,913 --> 00:16:13,379
I'm actually feeling a little faint.
Can we sit down?

267
00:16:13,447 --> 00:16:19,346
So, one thing I was wonderin'
is who's gonna be playing
the part of Sylvia Poston?

268
00:16:19,414 --> 00:16:21,709
[ Chuckles ]
Only Helen Sinclair.

269
00:16:21,780 --> 00:16:25,974
Helen Sinclair? [ Laughs ]
I never heard of her.

270
00:16:26,013 --> 00:16:30,638
- Uh, you follow the theater?
- What are you trying to insinuate?

271
00:16:30,713 --> 00:16:32,645
Hey, don't
gimme that shit!

272
00:16:32,713 --> 00:16:37,408
You tell Masucci he don't play
ball, I'll come down there,
I'll chop his fuckin' legs off!

273
00:16:37,480 --> 00:16:41,037
Don't you pay any attention to Nick.
He's in one of his depressed moods.

274
00:16:41,280 --> 00:16:45,474
I'll cut his throat. I'll come
down there, I'll pull his guts
out through his windpipe!

275
00:16:45,546 --> 00:16:47,671
- Ya hear me?
- What'd ya do? Walk up?

276
00:16:47,746 --> 00:16:49,678
- No!
- You're sweating like a pig.

277
00:16:49,746 --> 00:16:53,803
- I have a bit of a blood sugar
situation now and again.
- Blood sugar?

278
00:16:53,880 --> 00:16:57,573
- What is that?
- Olive, you-- you like the play?

279
00:16:57,646 --> 00:17:01,340
- Mmm. It's sad.
- Well, it's a tragedy.

280
00:17:01,380 --> 00:17:05,403
I'll say, but I got some ideas
how we can goose it up.

281
00:17:05,480 --> 00:17:08,071
- Ideas?
- Mm-hmm. I go to
the movies all the time.

282
00:17:08,314 --> 00:17:13,303
- I got a million clever ideas.
- You burn it down, Cheech!
Burn it down, I said.

283
00:17:13,380 --> 00:17:16,777
- I want it to look like arson!
- I got a crick.

284
00:17:16,846 --> 00:17:18,709
- When?
- A crick?

285
00:17:18,780 --> 00:17:23,304
Everything's tight.
I think maybe we should go.

286
00:17:23,347 --> 00:17:25,972
Oh, no, no, no.
Don't go.

287
00:17:26,047 --> 00:17:28,774
Hey, Venus, let's go
with that hooch!

288
00:17:28,846 --> 00:17:32,301
Uh, uh, Olive, when did you
get interested in acting?

289
00:17:32,380 --> 00:17:36,903
Hey, listen, you think
I came to this town to swing
it around in a chorus line?

290
00:17:36,980 --> 00:17:41,003
Tits and ass. Tits and ass.
That's all they care about. Thank you.

291
00:17:41,080 --> 00:17:44,069
Hey, didn't I tell you
to make "horse durves"?

292
00:17:44,314 --> 00:17:47,711
I don't make nothin' out of horses,
especially "horse durves..."

293
00:17:47,780 --> 00:17:50,406
'cause I don't know what
they are, and neither do you!

294
00:17:50,480 --> 00:17:54,536
Oh, ain't you the big mouth
since you hit your number.

295
00:17:54,613 --> 00:17:59,841
- And I said the imported stuff.
- The imported stuff ate through
the bottle. It's gone !

296
00:17:59,913 --> 00:18:02,970
A likely story. It's very hard
to get good help these days.

297
00:18:03,047 --> 00:18:05,911
- Sorry you guys had to hear that.
- I'm feeling fairly dizzy.

298
00:18:05,980 --> 00:18:10,776
- Some problems with the firm.
- Really? What type of firm is it, Nick?

299
00:18:10,846 --> 00:18:14,642
- [ Chuckles ]
- It's a "don't stick your nose in
other people's business...

300
00:18:14,680 --> 00:18:17,476
- and it won't get broken type of firm.
- Yeah.

301
00:18:17,513 --> 00:18:20,775
- [ Panting ] I see, I see. Thank you.
- That's what kind of firm.

302
00:18:20,846 --> 00:18:24,006
I'm feeling a bit unstable.
I think maybe I'll go...

303
00:18:24,080 --> 00:18:27,568
and check into a sanitarium
and get the help that I need.

304
00:18:27,646 --> 00:18:31,443
- And we'll talk later because
it's been good. Hasn't it, Julian?
- Yeah.

305
00:18:31,513 --> 00:18:33,446
- Oh, yeah.
- It's been good.

306
00:18:33,513 --> 00:18:36,775
- This is gonna be
a big event on Broadway.
- Thank you.

307
00:18:36,846 --> 00:18:39,744
Absolutely not!
No!

308
00:18:39,813 --> 00:18:42,836
- You'll work with her, mold her.
It'll be a challenge.
- Out of the question!

309
00:18:42,913 --> 00:18:45,970
She'll win an award. It'll be a great
show business anecdote.

310
00:18:46,047 --> 00:18:50,343
- It will not happen!
- A tribute to you as a director.
You use your actors like clay.

311
00:18:50,414 --> 00:18:53,073
Julian, have you lost
all reason?

312
00:18:53,314 --> 00:18:57,507
Do you believe that that woman
could play a psychiatrist?
That woman? That thing?

313
00:18:57,579 --> 00:18:59,511
- Her voice, her grasp.
- All right.

314
00:18:59,579 --> 00:19:04,478
- She's the woman who picks
quarters off tabletops with--
- Let me level with you.

315
00:19:04,513 --> 00:19:07,446
This is a dog-eat-dog world,
not an ideal world.

316
00:19:07,513 --> 00:19:10,480
If you wanna get your play on, you're
gonna have to make a few concessions.

317
00:19:10,546 --> 00:19:13,603
Life is not perfect.
Plus, it is short.

318
00:19:13,680 --> 00:19:18,045
If you can't figure that out,
you might as well pack up right
now and go back to Pittsburgh.

319
00:19:23,047 --> 00:19:27,412
- [ David Screaming ]
I sold out! I sold out.
- [ Ellen Gasping ]

320
00:19:27,480 --> 00:19:29,672
- I sold out.
- David.

321
00:19:29,746 --> 00:19:33,008
[ Panting ]

322
00:19:33,080 --> 00:19:35,671
- [ Gasps ]
- What's wrong?

323
00:19:35,746 --> 00:19:37,803
- [ Screaming ] I'm a whore!
- Oh, my God!

324
00:19:37,880 --> 00:19:40,971
- I'm a prostitute! I'm a whore!
- David, pull yourself together.

325
00:19:41,047 --> 00:19:42,706
- They'll call the police.
- [ Panting ]

326
00:19:42,780 --> 00:19:45,338
David. Oh, my God!
You look horrible.

327
00:19:45,414 --> 00:19:47,073
Oh, I feel sick.

328
00:19:47,314 --> 00:19:51,678
Please, you'll wake the Finkelsteins.
You want an aspirin?

329
00:19:51,746 --> 00:19:55,872
- David. David.
- Oh, my God! My art! My work!

330
00:19:55,946 --> 00:19:58,844
- What's wrong with you?
- Do I want success that badly?

331
00:19:58,913 --> 00:20:02,936
- David. Come back to bed.
- The answer's yes. The answer's yes.

332
00:20:03,013 --> 00:20:07,070
- Please come back to bed.
- When offered to have my play
backed by a hoodlum, I said yes.

333
00:20:07,314 --> 00:20:10,973
- Please come back to bed.
- It's a deal with the devil,
and the penalty is...

334
00:20:11,047 --> 00:20:14,945
- his girlfriend plays a part.
- Who are you calling at 3:00 a.m.?

335
00:20:15,013 --> 00:20:18,843
[ David ] Hello, Julian? It's David.
Who do you see in the male lead?

336
00:20:18,913 --> 00:20:21,572
Oh, kid.

337
00:20:21,646 --> 00:20:23,805
[ Groans ]
It's 3:00 a.m.

338
00:20:23,846 --> 00:20:27,040
- I see Warner Purcell.
- Nah, too fat.

339
00:20:27,280 --> 00:20:31,644
You seen him lately?
Nah, the man's a compulsive eater.

340
00:20:31,713 --> 00:20:33,645
Doesn't matter.
I talked to his agent...

341
00:20:33,680 --> 00:20:35,646
and he's been on a new diet
for four months. He looks fine.

342
00:20:35,680 --> 00:20:38,408
I want him for Lieutenant Masters.
Then maybe I can live with all this.

343
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:40,536
I can live with
these compromises.

344
00:20:40,613 --> 00:20:44,739
I'll have Warner Purcell
and Helen Sinclair, and then
I can live with that gun moll!

345
00:20:44,813 --> 00:20:47,677
No, not Warner, kid. No.

346
00:20:47,713 --> 00:20:50,043
I had him in Nuns Aplenty.

347
00:20:50,280 --> 00:20:54,507
He'll turn over a new leaf. Then he'll
get insecure; he'll start eating.

348
00:20:54,579 --> 00:20:58,773
By the time we get to Boston, he'll be
as big as my sister-in-law's ass.

349
00:20:58,846 --> 00:21:02,972
No! No more compromises!
It is my play, and I want him!

350
00:21:03,047 --> 00:21:06,672
I want him, and I want him,
and that's it. I'm not a whore!

351
00:21:06,746 --> 00:21:09,906
- David, David, David!
- [ Sighs ] I'm all right.

352
00:21:09,980 --> 00:21:13,605
[ Nick ] Olive starts rehearsal
for a show next week.

353
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:15,805
- I want you to stay with her.
- [ Cheech ] Yeah.

354
00:21:15,846 --> 00:21:18,835
I want you to make sure
they treat her right up there.

355
00:21:18,913 --> 00:21:21,777
Those theater characters
I don't trust 'em.

356
00:21:21,846 --> 00:21:25,835
The show's costing me a bundle,
and I'm gonna get my money's worth.

357
00:21:25,913 --> 00:21:28,879
- She wants to be a star.
- Yeah. Yeah.

358
00:21:28,946 --> 00:21:31,935
- And I promised her.
- Mr. V., look, it's not
that I don't wanna do it--

359
00:21:31,980 --> 00:21:36,379
Cheech, I'm giving you
an order. What do you do?

360
00:21:36,447 --> 00:21:38,470
I know.

361
00:21:38,546 --> 00:21:40,671
[ David ]
Monday, September 10.

362
00:21:40,746 --> 00:21:44,270
Today rehearsals began,
and I've decided to keep a journal.

363
00:21:44,347 --> 00:21:46,972
Perhaps my experience
will be of value to others...

364
00:21:47,013 --> 00:21:51,343
just as I pore over with relish
the notes of my idols:
Chekov and Strindberg.

365
00:21:51,414 --> 00:21:54,675
Rehearsals began promptly
at 10:00 a.m.

366
00:21:54,746 --> 00:21:58,610
Warner Purcell was first to arrive
full of bonhomie and good humor.

367
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:02,477
- Good morning!
- Warner Purcell.
Hello, I'm David Shayne.

368
00:22:02,546 --> 00:22:05,411
- Oh, David, how marvelous
to meet you. Well done.
- Thank you.

369
00:22:05,480 --> 00:22:08,536
- It's a wonderful play.
Some lovely speeches.
- I'm honored you're doing it.

370
00:22:08,613 --> 00:22:10,636
- It's my pleasure.
- Our stage manager, Mitch.

371
00:22:10,713 --> 00:22:13,441
- Mitchell Sabine.
I'm here if you need anything.
- Mitchell, nice to meet you.

372
00:22:13,513 --> 00:22:15,706
- That's fine.
- And you're gonna be
in dressing room two.

373
00:22:15,780 --> 00:22:17,939
- Lovely.
- And this is my assistant, Lorna.

374
00:22:18,013 --> 00:22:20,638
- Pleased to meet you.
- Lorna, nice to meet you.

375
00:22:20,713 --> 00:22:23,804
We have coffee and Danish,
some smoked salmon.

376
00:22:23,880 --> 00:22:28,074
Um, Mitchell, would it be
frightfully tiresome if I just
had hot water and lemon?

377
00:22:28,314 --> 00:22:30,303
- Not at all.
- Thank you.

378
00:22:30,380 --> 00:22:32,868
- And of course you know Julian Marx.
- Oh, Julian, yes.

379
00:22:32,946 --> 00:22:35,469
- Our swords have crossed.
- Warner, you look wonderful.

380
00:22:35,513 --> 00:22:37,638
- And yourself.
- [ Woman Giggling ]

381
00:22:37,713 --> 00:22:40,679
[ David ] Eden Brent, who plays
the other woman, arrived second.

382
00:22:40,713 --> 00:22:42,770
She has
a wonderful vivacity.

383
00:22:42,846 --> 00:22:46,642
[ Giggles ] Good morning! Good morning!
Don't get up. Don't get up.

384
00:22:46,680 --> 00:22:49,840
- I have first-day-rehearsal
presents for everybody.
- How thoughtful.

385
00:22:49,880 --> 00:22:54,710
It's nothing. Just some soap and some
potpourri and incense for you, I think.

386
00:22:54,780 --> 00:22:57,940
- Now, have you met Mr. Woofles?
- No. No.

387
00:22:58,013 --> 00:23:01,377
- Oh, don't pull such a sour face.
- Hello, Mr. Woofles.

388
00:23:01,447 --> 00:23:03,379
Oh, be careful.
She's a Chihuahua...

389
00:23:03,447 --> 00:23:07,503
but there's a pinch of Doberman in her
so sometimes she goes for your throat.

390
00:23:07,579 --> 00:23:09,704
- Just kidding.
- [ Laughs ]

391
00:23:09,780 --> 00:23:13,372
- I think you've met
everyone here. Lorna.
- We talked on the telephone.

392
00:23:13,447 --> 00:23:16,277
I don't know if you've met
our Lieutenant Masters, Warner Purcell.

393
00:23:16,347 --> 00:23:18,744
- Oh, pleased to meet you.
- How was your crossing?

394
00:23:18,813 --> 00:23:22,506
- Well, I came over
five years ago, but it was lovely.
- [ Giggles ]

395
00:23:22,579 --> 00:23:25,636
Now, my darling, do you want
some milk or something to eat?

396
00:23:25,713 --> 00:23:29,839
- I'll get her a saucer.
- You don't have to bother with
that because I breast-feed her.

397
00:23:29,913 --> 00:23:33,606
- Just kidding, everybody.
- [ Laughing ]

398
00:23:33,680 --> 00:23:35,873
- Please.
- Julian, nice to see you.

399
00:23:35,946 --> 00:23:38,378
- How are you?
- Mr. Marx.
- Yes, of course.

400
00:23:38,447 --> 00:23:41,072
I'm in the middle, yes?

401
00:23:41,314 --> 00:23:43,973
- [ David ] Should we take the dog--
- No, no, no, no, no.

402
00:23:44,047 --> 00:23:46,842
It's my baby.
[ Giggles ]

403
00:23:46,913 --> 00:23:50,845
[ David ] Olive Neal entered, naturally,
with the force of a hurricane.

404
00:23:50,880 --> 00:23:55,279
- Hey, you gonna hover
over me like dead meat?
- Mr. V. says I stay close.

405
00:23:55,347 --> 00:23:57,279
We've been drivin'
around for 15 minutes.

406
00:23:57,347 --> 00:24:01,074
I told ya he said the Belasco,
not the Morosco, you cementhead!

407
00:24:01,314 --> 00:24:02,677
- Hello, Olive.
- Hello.

408
00:24:02,746 --> 00:24:05,940
- Everyone, this is Dr. Philips.
Olive Neal.
- Hi, nice to meet you.

409
00:24:06,013 --> 00:24:07,501
- You know Julian.
- Yes.

410
00:24:07,579 --> 00:24:09,568
- My assistant, Lorna.
- Hi.

411
00:24:09,646 --> 00:24:11,771
- Eden Brent, Kristen.
- Ah, cute dog.

412
00:24:11,846 --> 00:24:14,438
- Warner Purcell. Lieutenant Masters.
- Charmed, charmed, charmed.

413
00:24:14,513 --> 00:24:16,945
- Stage manager Mitch.
- Mitch, hi, hi, hi, hi.

414
00:24:17,013 --> 00:24:19,774
- And you are?
- I'm with her.

415
00:24:19,846 --> 00:24:22,835
- He's with me. Yeah.
- Okay. Okay.

416
00:24:22,913 --> 00:24:26,311
Well, um, we're just gonna
rehearse for a while, so--

417
00:24:26,347 --> 00:24:28,313
Yeah.
Where she goes, I go.

418
00:24:28,347 --> 00:24:31,336
All right, buster,
why don't you park yourself in
the back row of the theater...

419
00:24:31,414 --> 00:24:33,346
and try not to snore.

420
00:24:33,414 --> 00:24:35,879
Um, I--

421
00:24:35,946 --> 00:24:38,935
- What?
- I don't like other people
watching rehearsals...

422
00:24:39,013 --> 00:24:42,809
- generally as a rule because
the actors are very sensitive.
- What'd you say?

423
00:24:42,880 --> 00:24:46,313
- I-I don't like--
- Hey, hey, who are you? Who are you?

424
00:24:46,347 --> 00:24:48,336
- Whoa, whoa. Easy.
- I'm the director.

425
00:24:48,380 --> 00:24:49,811
- Who is this?
- Wait a minute.

426
00:24:49,880 --> 00:24:52,778
- I'm the director of the play.
- Wait a minute, Mr., uh--

427
00:24:52,813 --> 00:24:55,711
- Cheech. The name's Cheech.
- Mr. Cheech, first of all--

428
00:24:55,780 --> 00:24:58,474
- No, not Mr. Cheech. Ya hear me?
- Yeah.

429
00:24:58,546 --> 00:25:01,479
- Cheech. Simple. Cheech.
- Cheech.

430
00:25:01,546 --> 00:25:05,842
Now, why don't you just take a seat
in the back and we'll-- Yeah, go ahead.

431
00:25:05,880 --> 00:25:08,472
- That's it.
- I find this very problematic.

432
00:25:08,546 --> 00:25:10,705
- I'll be over there.
- He'll be unobtrusive, believe me.

433
00:25:10,780 --> 00:25:14,440
He's not gonna bother anybody.
He just wants to watch.

434
00:25:14,513 --> 00:25:17,480
He's my bodyguard.
[ Giggles ]

435
00:25:17,546 --> 00:25:19,944
- Hi.
- Hello.

436
00:25:20,013 --> 00:25:24,536
- Sorry I'm late.
I'm usually highly professional.
- Oh, I'm sure.

437
00:25:24,613 --> 00:25:28,807
- This is for you.
- Oh, talcum powder. My favorite.

438
00:25:28,846 --> 00:25:32,608
- Thank you. You're a doll.
- Oh, no, you're a doll.

439
00:25:32,646 --> 00:25:36,409
[ David ] Helen Sinclair came a half
hour late, but she had a good excuse.

440
00:25:36,480 --> 00:25:40,037
Please forgive me.
My pedicurist had a stroke.

441
00:25:40,280 --> 00:25:43,734
She fell forward onto the orange stick
and plunged it into my toe.

442
00:25:43,813 --> 00:25:46,677
- It required bandaging.
- Oh, my poor darling.

443
00:25:46,746 --> 00:25:49,304
Oh, it's so good
to see you.

444
00:25:49,347 --> 00:25:52,006
- We all know and admire Helen Sinclair.
- [ Warner ] We're old friends.

445
00:25:52,080 --> 00:25:54,841
- Thank you so much.
- Miss Sinclair, this is Mitch.

446
00:25:54,913 --> 00:25:59,971
Oh, yes, yes. Oh, my goodness' sake.
I can't believe I'm here.

447
00:26:00,047 --> 00:26:03,979
Oh-ho, look at this.
Look at this. Would you look?

448
00:26:04,013 --> 00:26:06,706
Oh, this old theater.

449
00:26:08,447 --> 00:26:10,470
This church.

450
00:26:11,579 --> 00:26:13,977
So replete
with memories.

451
00:26:14,047 --> 00:26:17,411
So full of ghosts.

452
00:26:17,480 --> 00:26:19,809
Mrs. Alving.

453
00:26:19,880 --> 00:26:21,846
Uncle Vanya.

454
00:26:22,880 --> 00:26:25,312
There's Cordelia.

455
00:26:26,013 --> 00:26:28,501
Here's Ophelia.

456
00:26:30,047 --> 00:26:32,377
Clytemenstra!

457
00:26:33,946 --> 00:26:36,412
Each performance
a birth.

458
00:26:37,513 --> 00:26:39,809
Each curtain...

459
00:26:39,880 --> 00:26:41,937
a death.

460
00:26:42,013 --> 00:26:44,706
[ Mr. Woofles Barking ]

461
00:26:44,780 --> 00:26:46,973
Was that a mutt?

462
00:26:47,047 --> 00:26:49,672
[ Mitch ]
Yes, Miss Sinclair.

463
00:26:49,746 --> 00:26:53,872
- I hate mutts!
- [ Barking Continues ]

464
00:26:53,946 --> 00:26:56,935
[ David ] I didn't want to overwhelm
any of the actors on the first day...

465
00:26:57,013 --> 00:26:59,638
so all we did
was read through the play.

466
00:26:59,713 --> 00:27:01,906
I can't live
like this.

467
00:27:01,980 --> 00:27:05,435
The same routine
over and over and over.

468
00:27:05,513 --> 00:27:07,877
The days blend together
like melted celluloid.

469
00:27:07,946 --> 00:27:11,503
Like a film whose images
become distorted and meaningless.

470
00:27:11,579 --> 00:27:14,807
I want a divorce, Sylvia. I've said it
in a thousand subtle ways...

471
00:27:14,880 --> 00:27:17,937
hoping you would realize,
but you refuse to see it.

472
00:27:18,013 --> 00:27:20,979
As a little girl,
I swore one day...

473
00:27:21,047 --> 00:27:24,377
I would have a necklace
made from the Milky Way.

474
00:27:24,447 --> 00:27:29,777
Oh, Kristen, Kristen, if only humans
weren't cursed with the power of memory.

475
00:27:29,846 --> 00:27:33,505
[ Olive Reading Flatly ]
Dreams are only disguised feelings.

476
00:27:33,579 --> 00:27:37,875
The more we bring these
painful experiences to the fore...

477
00:27:37,946 --> 00:27:40,810
the easier they become
to deal with.

478
00:27:40,880 --> 00:27:43,438
- What's the "fore"?
- The fore. The foreground.

479
00:27:43,513 --> 00:27:45,604
- [ Warner ] Is it-- Could I?
- [ David ] Please.

480
00:27:45,680 --> 00:27:49,612
It's a golf term, when you yell, "fore"
when you're coming forward.

481
00:27:49,680 --> 00:27:53,443
- [ Helen ] I didn't realize that.
- So you're telling me
she's talking about golf?

482
00:27:53,513 --> 00:27:54,774
- Continue!
- What?

483
00:27:54,846 --> 00:27:57,472
[ Helen ]
Oh, yes, okay. Doctor...

484
00:27:57,513 --> 00:28:00,741
am I unattractive,
worn out?

485
00:28:00,813 --> 00:28:04,939
Spent? Broken?
Desiccated? Old?

486
00:28:05,013 --> 00:28:09,275
[ Olive ] Come, come, Mrs. Poston.
You're being mas--

487
00:28:10,579 --> 00:28:12,478
- Mas--
- [ David ] Masochistic.

488
00:28:12,546 --> 00:28:17,445
- Masochistic?
- Yes, masochism is someone
who enjoys pain.

489
00:28:17,513 --> 00:28:20,412
- [ Warner ] As opposed to sadism.
- Enjoys pain?

490
00:28:20,480 --> 00:28:22,604
What is she,
retarded?

491
00:28:22,646 --> 00:28:25,737
- I don't fuckin' believe this!
- Continue.

492
00:28:25,813 --> 00:28:29,041
[ David ] After the rehearsal,
I felt exhilarated.

493
00:28:29,280 --> 00:28:31,768
Helen Sinclair suggested
we go for a drink to unwind.

494
00:28:31,813 --> 00:28:36,075
She said she knew
of a little out-of-the-way
speakeasy where we could talk.

495
00:28:36,314 --> 00:28:38,779
- It was wonderful to see old, uh--
- Wasn't it?

496
00:28:38,846 --> 00:28:42,301
- Warner. Yes.
- Warner, yeah. He looks so slim.

497
00:28:42,347 --> 00:28:45,472
- He's on a new diet.
- Who is she? Oh, I need a drink.

498
00:28:45,546 --> 00:28:47,671
Olive. [ Chuckles ]
Yes. I'm sorry about Olive.

499
00:28:47,746 --> 00:28:50,474
I do apologize.
We needed her to raise the money.

500
00:28:50,546 --> 00:28:52,876
It must be difficult
getting a work like this on.

501
00:28:52,946 --> 00:28:55,412
It's a sad reality
of the marketplace, I'll tell ya.

502
00:28:55,480 --> 00:28:57,911
- We've never really
had a chance to talk.
- No.

503
00:28:57,980 --> 00:29:01,571
- Hi, folks. What can I get you?
- Two martinis, please, very dry.

504
00:29:01,646 --> 00:29:04,976
- How'd you know what I drank?
- Oh, you want one too?

505
00:29:05,013 --> 00:29:07,002
- Three.
- Three martinis.

506
00:29:07,080 --> 00:29:10,568
Uh, I can't judge my own writing,
but I must say...

507
00:29:10,646 --> 00:29:14,806
that just from today's reading,
I can tell how brilliant
you're going to be in this role.

508
00:29:14,880 --> 00:29:16,743
- It's a wonderful play.
- Thank you.

509
00:29:16,813 --> 00:29:20,870
No, no, I mean it. It's so rare
that anything is really about something.

510
00:29:20,946 --> 00:29:23,878
You know-- Well, there's Max Anderson
and Gene O'Neill.

511
00:29:23,946 --> 00:29:26,469
- That's about it.
- You just named my two living gods.

512
00:29:26,513 --> 00:29:29,480
I was a little reluctant at first
to play the part.

513
00:29:29,513 --> 00:29:33,809
The character is so--
She's so, um... uh, colorless.

514
00:29:33,880 --> 00:29:35,539
Colorless, yes.
Well, that's the idea--

515
00:29:35,613 --> 00:29:37,602
- Then I realized what
you were going for.
- You did?

516
00:29:37,680 --> 00:29:39,839
How profound, how complex,
her inner life really is.

517
00:29:39,913 --> 00:29:42,379
I tried to give her
some contradictions.

518
00:29:42,447 --> 00:29:44,413
I was worried.

519
00:29:44,480 --> 00:29:48,469
I'm used to playing
more overtly heroic women.

520
00:29:48,513 --> 00:29:51,309
Less tentative.
More alluring.

521
00:29:51,380 --> 00:29:53,777
Certainly not
frigid.

522
00:29:53,846 --> 00:29:59,074
No, yes, yes. Well, Sylvia Poston
is a mass of neuroses.

523
00:29:59,314 --> 00:30:03,371
In spite of the fact that I
could really find nothing at all
in the play to brighten her up...

524
00:30:03,447 --> 00:30:06,571
- no real passion, no seductiveness...
- Nothing?

525
00:30:06,646 --> 00:30:08,942
I still think that
she's worth playing.

526
00:30:09,013 --> 00:30:13,070
We could work it over, and
a touch here or there could be
changed to make sure you're...

527
00:30:13,314 --> 00:30:16,405
- No, no, no, no.
I wouldn't dream of you...
- comfortable.

528
00:30:16,480 --> 00:30:19,002
changing a word
of your work for me.

529
00:30:19,080 --> 00:30:24,274
God, who am l, some
vain Broadway legend?

530
00:30:24,347 --> 00:30:28,074
You... you're
a budding Chekhov.

531
00:30:31,347 --> 00:30:36,370
I'm not saying I'll distort the play.
I'm just saying I'll reread it
with that in mind.

532
00:30:36,447 --> 00:30:39,503
I mean, after all, Miss Sinclair--
Helen. May I call you Helen?

533
00:30:39,579 --> 00:30:41,704
- Yes.
- Helen...

534
00:30:41,780 --> 00:30:44,905
your instincts as an actress
are impeccable.

535
00:30:44,980 --> 00:30:49,708
And I want the character
to have dimension. I don't mean
for her to be a drone.

536
00:30:50,813 --> 00:30:53,973
- You see through me, don't you?
- Me?

537
00:30:54,013 --> 00:30:56,343
You're clever.

538
00:30:56,414 --> 00:30:58,641
You're brilliant.

539
00:30:58,680 --> 00:31:01,306
What insight
into women.

540
00:31:01,380 --> 00:31:03,437
Don't deny it.

541
00:31:08,480 --> 00:31:11,536
I don't see why
she has to be frigid.

542
00:31:15,980 --> 00:31:19,310
[ Nick ] Hey, how ya doin', doll?
How'd it go?

543
00:31:19,347 --> 00:31:21,642
[ Olive ] Ah, they're all
so stuck up.

544
00:31:21,713 --> 00:31:24,577
- Yeah? Anybody botherin' her?
- No.

545
00:31:24,646 --> 00:31:27,477
They expect me to memorize
all these lines.

546
00:31:27,513 --> 00:31:31,310
- Well, that's what you wanted,
isn't it? To be an actress?
- I know, I know, I know.

547
00:31:31,347 --> 00:31:34,904
- I got a headache.
- Cheech'll help you
practice after we eat.

548
00:31:34,980 --> 00:31:38,571
- Me?
- The girl's got stuff
to memorize, all right?

549
00:31:38,646 --> 00:31:41,908
- Yeah, but, Nick--
- Go sit in the tub, honey. Go ahead.

550
00:31:41,980 --> 00:31:45,707
I'm takin' you out to Delmonico's.
You want sirloin or a lobster?

551
00:31:45,780 --> 00:31:49,440
- One of each.
- Listen, Nick, I'm not too good
at this memorizing, and I got a date--

552
00:31:49,513 --> 00:31:53,378
All right, all right, knock it off.
I got a little errand for you to run.

553
00:31:53,447 --> 00:31:58,277
- What kind of errand?
- A message for Charlie Masucci,
and we ain't got a lot of time.

554
00:31:59,414 --> 00:32:14,269
##

555
00:32:17,380 --> 00:32:21,937
Up a lazy river
where the old mill run

556
00:32:21,980 --> 00:32:26,810
Meets lazy, lazy river
in the noonday sun

557
00:32:26,846 --> 00:32:31,574
Linger in the shade
of a kind old tree

558
00:32:31,646 --> 00:32:34,442
Throw away your troubles
Dream a dream--

559
00:32:37,347 --> 00:32:40,904
- Up a lazy river
where the robin's song
- [ Water Splashing ]

560
00:32:40,980 --> 00:32:43,071
Awakes a bright
new morning--

561
00:32:43,314 --> 00:32:45,677
Can't you see...

562
00:32:45,713 --> 00:32:48,907
you're living out
the exact same pattern...

563
00:32:48,980 --> 00:32:51,673
your mother lived out
with your father?

564
00:32:51,746 --> 00:32:54,837
I am?
Pray tell.

565
00:32:54,913 --> 00:32:58,277
In some way,
you're trying to relive it,

566
00:32:58,347 --> 00:33:02,404
and in the process
of reliving it, correct it.

567
00:33:02,480 --> 00:33:05,968
As if that were possible.
Ha!

568
00:33:06,047 --> 00:33:09,275
-It don't say "Ha."
-I know it don't say "Ha." I added that.

569
00:33:09,347 --> 00:33:12,540
- What do ya mean you added that?
Are you allowed to do that?
- We're allowed to add things.

570
00:33:12,613 --> 00:33:15,011
- How could you add something?
You can't do that.
- You're allowed!

571
00:33:15,080 --> 00:33:17,511
- It's called ad-libbing.
- You can't do that!

572
00:33:17,579 --> 00:33:20,943
I can do that. What do you know? You
don't know nothin'. Shut up and read.

573
00:33:21,013 --> 00:33:24,604
- I think the whole thing stinks.
- I think you're a degenerate
zombie. Shut up and read!

574
00:33:24,680 --> 00:33:27,374
- You better shut up! Just shut up!
- You shut up and read.

575
00:33:27,447 --> 00:33:30,379
- You shut up!
- You're lucky you're Nick's girl.

576
00:33:30,447 --> 00:33:32,379
You're lucky
you're an idiot.

577
00:33:32,447 --> 00:33:37,311
What endeavors you...
to concoct a theory so tenuous?

578
00:33:37,347 --> 00:33:39,074
Mmm-mmm-mm.

579
00:33:39,314 --> 00:33:43,303
I sure pities the poor folks who gonna
have to pay to see this play.

580
00:33:45,480 --> 00:33:49,412
- What ya thinking?
- Oh, just about Eugene O'Neill
and Max Anderson, you know.

581
00:33:49,480 --> 00:33:52,877
Yeah. You've been rewriting all night
and it's only just the first day.

582
00:33:52,946 --> 00:33:55,310
- Is that a bad sign?
- No. I just think that
I might have made...

583
00:33:55,380 --> 00:33:57,743
the character of Sylvia Poston
a bit too antiseptic.

584
00:33:57,813 --> 00:33:59,870
- She's gotta have a sexual side to her.
- No.

585
00:33:59,946 --> 00:34:04,345
- I think she's the best female
character you've written in a long time.
- Says who?

586
00:34:04,414 --> 00:34:07,777
David, you know you always have
problems getting into the female mind.

587
00:34:07,846 --> 00:34:11,801
- I know that you think that.
- You've said so yourself before.
We've had this discussion.

588
00:34:11,880 --> 00:34:16,472
All your friends are men. You-- You've
always had problems writing for women.

589
00:34:16,546 --> 00:34:19,342
Witness your relationship
with your mother, your grandmother...

590
00:34:19,414 --> 00:34:22,504
- your two aunts, your sister--
- I think I try to factor that
into my work.

591
00:34:22,579 --> 00:34:24,511
But to be honest with you...

592
00:34:24,579 --> 00:34:26,511
at this moment, I don't think
you really understand my work at all.

593
00:34:26,579 --> 00:34:28,636
- Oh! Don't be so defensive.
- I'm not being defensive.

594
00:34:28,713 --> 00:34:32,645
Perhaps my opinions just aren't
intellectual enough for you.
Maybe they're just not--

595
00:34:32,713 --> 00:34:36,873
That's a horrible thing to say.
When you have a good idea,
I listen to it. I'm responsive.

596
00:34:36,946 --> 00:34:40,401
- In this case, I think you're
wrong. That's about it.
- When am I right?

597
00:34:40,480 --> 00:34:43,912
You're right about other things, but not
about Sylvia Poston and her sexuality.

598
00:34:43,980 --> 00:34:47,537
[ David ] September 17.
The first week is behind me now...

599
00:34:47,613 --> 00:34:51,444
and apart from a few minor incidents,
things seemed to go okay.

600
00:34:51,480 --> 00:34:53,945
There was that moment
between Helen and Eden.

601
00:34:54,013 --> 00:34:57,911
I can't do that speech if she's
going to be fidgeting around upstage!

602
00:34:57,980 --> 00:35:00,571
- Well, that's why I think
I should sit. I'll sit.
- Oh, God!

603
00:35:00,646 --> 00:35:04,272
Sylvia would never ask her to sit
in her own house. She despises her!

604
00:35:04,347 --> 00:35:08,006
She doesn't want me to sit. She doesn't
want me to stand. I guess I could squat.

605
00:35:08,047 --> 00:35:11,275
David, do you realize you're asking an
audience to believe that my husband...

606
00:35:11,314 --> 00:35:13,303
would leave me
for this woman?

607
00:35:13,380 --> 00:35:17,278
- Come along.
- Excuse me. Excuse me, but
I think it's made very clear...

608
00:35:17,347 --> 00:35:20,074
in the speech about erotic attraction,
why he does that.

609
00:35:20,314 --> 00:35:22,779
You fool! He's thinking of me
when he does that speech.
Don't you know anything?

610
00:35:22,813 --> 00:35:25,279
- Only the part about the liver spots.
- Listen.

611
00:35:25,347 --> 00:35:29,302
How long has it been since
you've had a real hemorrhage?

612
00:35:29,347 --> 00:35:33,370
David, I wonder if now would be a moment
to do my soliloquy from Act II?

613
00:35:33,447 --> 00:35:38,470
- [ Crying ] Did you hear what she--
- Please. Aspirin!

614
00:35:38,513 --> 00:35:42,276
[ David ] All right, yes, why don't we?
And, Eden, just take five.

615
00:35:42,314 --> 00:35:45,007
- I need an aspirin!
- [ Crying Continues ]

616
00:35:45,080 --> 00:35:48,012
[ David ]
Mitch.

617
00:35:48,047 --> 00:35:51,638
[ David ] Then there was the time when
I tried to cut one of Olive's speeches.

618
00:35:51,713 --> 00:35:55,770
- I like that speech,
and I already got it memorized.
- But it's superfluous.

619
00:35:55,846 --> 00:35:58,573
- It's-- What is it?
- Well, I've overwritten it.

620
00:35:58,646 --> 00:36:02,976
We know how you feel
about Sylvia's breakdown when
you talk with the good doctor.

621
00:36:03,047 --> 00:36:05,842
So it's my fault.
Um, the performance is fine.

622
00:36:05,913 --> 00:36:09,004
But, um...
I like to say it.

623
00:36:09,080 --> 00:36:11,568
- We-- We don't need it.
- Hey!

624
00:36:11,646 --> 00:36:14,669
Are you tryin' to make
my part smaller?

625
00:36:14,746 --> 00:36:17,304
- No, no, every--
- My part's small enough as it is!

626
00:36:17,380 --> 00:36:20,971
Every play needs some cuts, and the size
of the role is not the important thing.

627
00:36:21,047 --> 00:36:24,638
Did you hear what she said? She doesn't
want her speech taken away from her!

628
00:36:24,713 --> 00:36:29,271
- Look, look, Mr. Cheech, I've about--
- I'd rather be shootin' crap myself...

629
00:36:29,347 --> 00:36:33,938
but Mr. V. told me that she's gotta
be up there a lot!

630
00:36:34,013 --> 00:36:36,638
- I wrote this play,
and I'm directing this play!
- I don't care.

631
00:36:36,713 --> 00:36:40,668
You wanna get slapped here or do
you want me to take you outside
and we'll straighten this out?

632
00:36:40,746 --> 00:36:43,440
It's up to you.

633
00:36:46,680 --> 00:36:50,443
[ David ] Warner Purcell remains
good-spirited and a joy to work with.

634
00:36:50,513 --> 00:36:55,844
And what discipline. Although,
I notice he no longer has just
a cup of hot water and lemon.

635
00:36:58,080 --> 00:37:02,012
[ Eden ] lf you start it off
at that level--

636
00:37:02,080 --> 00:37:06,808
Well, what are we going to do
about that canine-loving ingenue?

637
00:37:06,846 --> 00:37:09,778
- Did you cast her because
you thought she was attractive?
- She's pretty...

638
00:37:09,846 --> 00:37:13,472
but more importantly, she has a certain
perkiness that the character requires.

639
00:37:13,546 --> 00:37:17,445
She's perky. She makes you
wanna sneak up behind her with
a pillow and suffocate her.

640
00:37:17,513 --> 00:37:19,877
- It's a beautiful apartment.
- Josette.

641
00:37:19,946 --> 00:37:22,776
- My beaker of martinis.
- Your taste is exquisite.

642
00:37:22,813 --> 00:37:27,269
My taste is superb.
My eyes are exquisite.

643
00:37:27,347 --> 00:37:29,472
What justifiable confidence.

644
00:37:29,513 --> 00:37:33,071
- I think at some point you're
going to have to fire Olive.
- I'm afraid that's not possible.

645
00:37:33,314 --> 00:37:37,871
Oh, how can you take her butchering
your poetry? I know I couldn't stand it.

646
00:37:37,946 --> 00:37:42,038
No one in his right mind is
going to believe she's a doctor,
not even a veterinarian.

647
00:37:42,280 --> 00:37:45,337
- [ Chuckles ]
- I understand, but it's a compromise
I have to live with...

648
00:37:45,414 --> 00:37:47,811
and if I want the play to open,
I have to find a way to live with it.

649
00:37:47,880 --> 00:37:50,403
I plan on reducing the scope of her role
if her bodyguard will let me.

650
00:37:50,480 --> 00:37:52,412
Can you believe
that character?

651
00:37:52,480 --> 00:37:55,570
Imagine, traveling with
your own private Neanderthal.

652
00:37:55,646 --> 00:37:58,578
- I wasn't aware that you opened
The Master Builder.
- Oh, well.

653
00:37:58,646 --> 00:38:01,874
I had forgotten that
you won that drama award.

654
00:38:01,946 --> 00:38:04,810
- Here's to your play.
- Oh, thank you. Our play.

655
00:38:04,846 --> 00:38:08,676
To an ideal world
with no compromise.

656
00:38:12,980 --> 00:38:15,946
Oh, my gosh,
look at this view!

657
00:38:16,013 --> 00:38:20,741
A million blinking lights.
A million broken hearts.

658
00:38:20,813 --> 00:38:23,336
- You know what's down there?
- What?

659
00:38:23,414 --> 00:38:26,471
- Broadway.
- Ah. That's your street.

660
00:38:26,546 --> 00:38:31,604
Mm-hmm. Yes, that's my street,
but I'd like to give it to you.

661
00:38:31,680 --> 00:38:35,635
- That is, if you want it.
- Who wouldn't want it?

662
00:38:35,713 --> 00:38:39,476
I want you to write a play for me.
Oh, I mean when all this is over.

663
00:38:39,513 --> 00:38:43,310
- Really?
- Your next play, I want you to create
a vehicle for Helen Sinclair.

664
00:38:43,380 --> 00:38:46,573
- I'm honored.
- But it must have size...

665
00:38:46,646 --> 00:38:48,771
an important woman.

666
00:38:48,846 --> 00:38:52,505
- A Borgia. A Curie. You name it.
- Yes!

667
00:38:52,579 --> 00:38:55,511
- I'll dedicate myself to it.
- Oh, and while you're at it...

668
00:38:55,579 --> 00:38:58,841
if you could just have
a look at that scene in Act ll.

669
00:38:58,880 --> 00:39:03,074
If she succeeds in seducing
the Lieutenant instead of
being rejected a second time...

670
00:39:03,314 --> 00:39:08,474
- it could add some variation
to the character.
- Yes, that's a wonderful idea.

671
00:39:08,513 --> 00:39:11,002
The heart is "labyrinthinine..."

672
00:39:11,080 --> 00:39:15,410
a maze beset with brutal pitfalls
and mean obstacles.

673
00:39:15,480 --> 00:39:19,878
David, I can't say that line. It doesn't
make sense. It's stupid. I don't get it.

674
00:39:19,946 --> 00:39:23,605
- It's just a stylish way
of expressing a particular idea.
- Idea? What idea?

675
00:39:23,680 --> 00:39:25,805
The agony of love.
The difficulty of relating.

676
00:39:25,846 --> 00:39:28,539
- Why do you have to make it
so hard to say?
- Just say the line.

677
00:39:28,613 --> 00:39:31,602
- No, I can't say it.
It's a mouthful of "ghibberish."
- Gibberish!

678
00:39:31,646 --> 00:39:34,442
- I can't say it, and I will not say it.
- Just do the line.

679
00:39:34,513 --> 00:39:36,446
No! I'm not making
a fool of myself.

680
00:39:36,513 --> 00:39:38,446
[ Cheech ]
She's right, it stinks.

681
00:39:38,513 --> 00:39:40,945
Oh-ho, Jesus,
another party heard from.

682
00:39:40,980 --> 00:39:43,639
It's a stupid way of talkin',
and nobody talks like that.

683
00:39:43,713 --> 00:39:46,077
- I don't believe this is happening.
- Frankenstein is right.

684
00:39:46,314 --> 00:39:48,303
When I want your opinion,
I will ask for it.

685
00:39:48,347 --> 00:39:51,074
I can't stand to listen to this
garbage. Every day I sit back there...

686
00:39:51,314 --> 00:39:53,075
and I hear the same bullshit
over and over again.

687
00:39:53,314 --> 00:39:55,075
Then leave.
No one asked you here.

688
00:39:55,314 --> 00:39:56,973
[ Helen ]
Oh, David, take it easy.

689
00:39:57,013 --> 00:39:59,411
Where did you study play writing?
Was it Sing Sing?

690
00:39:59,480 --> 00:40:01,809
"A maze beset
by brutal pitfalls--"

691
00:40:01,846 --> 00:40:04,438
Hey, Olive, I memorized it,
and I'm tellin' ya...

692
00:40:04,513 --> 00:40:07,946
it comes to me all the time,
and it stinks on fuckin' hot ice!

693
00:40:08,013 --> 00:40:10,979
- That's it. I quit. This is crazy.
- [ Warner ] David.

694
00:40:11,047 --> 00:40:14,740
- Oh, please, I have a little hangover!
- I am famished.

695
00:40:14,813 --> 00:40:17,870
Everyone, everyone,
why don't we take lunch? An hour?

696
00:40:17,946 --> 00:40:20,810
- [ Mr. Woofles Barking ]
- You don't wanna
say the goddamned line...

697
00:40:20,846 --> 00:40:24,074
- don't say the goddamned line!
- Oh, look at you, Mr. Temperamental.

698
00:40:24,314 --> 00:40:27,905
[ Helen ] lf that rat on a leash
barks one more time--

699
00:40:27,980 --> 00:40:30,878
-He sounds melancholy. Is he melancholy?
-You can trim the line.

700
00:40:30,946 --> 00:40:34,401
- Because she can't handle it?
- Because you said yourself
you were having trouble with it.

701
00:40:34,480 --> 00:40:36,707
- So you agree with the gorilla?
- David, for Christ sake! It's one line!

702
00:40:36,780 --> 00:40:38,973
- It's not going to wreck the scene.
- That's not the point!

703
00:40:39,013 --> 00:40:42,468
Suddenly I'm taking suggestions from a
strong-arm man with an I.Q. of minus 50.

704
00:40:42,546 --> 00:40:44,512
I've had it!

705
00:40:44,546 --> 00:40:47,842
- David, for goodness' sake. Come on.
- Look who's here.

706
00:40:47,913 --> 00:40:50,743
Oh, God!
Get my rifle!

707
00:40:50,813 --> 00:40:54,337
I guess I'm just hypersensitive because
maybe deep down, I agree with the goon.

708
00:40:54,414 --> 00:40:58,812
- Maybe it is a turgid line.
I don't know. My nerves are shot.
- No. Just calm yourself.

709
00:40:58,846 --> 00:41:03,540
Helen, the play is not working.
It's not working, and it's in my
writing. It's not just Olive.

710
00:41:03,613 --> 00:41:07,807
That's the reason we have rehearsal.
That's the reason we go out of town.

711
00:41:09,780 --> 00:41:13,269
You have such a wonderful attitude.
I'm so lucky.

712
00:41:13,347 --> 00:41:15,972
The best part of this project every day
is that I get to come to work...

713
00:41:16,047 --> 00:41:18,945
and see you and be with you
and work with you.

714
00:41:19,013 --> 00:41:23,502
- I don't mean to spoil the day.
- Then let's not.

715
00:41:23,579 --> 00:41:26,875
Sit down here.
I'm going to show you something.

716
00:41:26,946 --> 00:41:28,844
Okay.

717
00:41:29,913 --> 00:41:32,777
This is my favorite spot
in the park.

718
00:41:34,780 --> 00:41:38,008
And in winter,
when it's covered with snow...

719
00:41:38,080 --> 00:41:42,774
at about 4:30 in the afternoon,
when it's just getting dark
and the lights come on...

720
00:41:42,813 --> 00:41:44,779
it's all misty.

721
00:41:44,846 --> 00:41:49,744
And you can just see the silhouettes of
the Manhattan skyline through the trees.

722
00:41:49,813 --> 00:41:52,302
And it's magical.

723
00:41:52,380 --> 00:41:54,709
It's magical.

724
00:41:56,447 --> 00:41:59,038
Helen, I think I'm falling
in love with you.

725
00:41:59,280 --> 00:42:01,075
Don't.

726
00:42:01,314 --> 00:42:05,303
- I don't know if I can help it.
- David, please, we must be strong.

727
00:42:05,380 --> 00:42:08,937
I've kept a check on my feelings
for so long, but there's
so much that I want to say.

728
00:42:09,013 --> 00:42:11,604
- What are words?
- Oh, gosh.

729
00:42:11,680 --> 00:42:14,942
David, everything meaningful
is in some unexplainable form.

730
00:42:15,013 --> 00:42:19,275
It's-- It's more primordial
than mere language.

731
00:42:19,347 --> 00:42:21,710
- I'm not sure I follow that one.
- Oh, be silent.

732
00:42:21,780 --> 00:42:23,746
- Be silent.
- Helen--

733
00:42:23,813 --> 00:42:26,904
No, let's just sit here
holding our thoughts.

734
00:42:26,980 --> 00:42:29,810
Not revealing them.
Be still.

735
00:42:29,880 --> 00:42:34,642
Let the birds have their song.
Let ours for now remain unsung.

736
00:42:34,713 --> 00:42:36,838
You're amazing.

737
00:42:36,913 --> 00:42:40,811
[ "Ain't Misbehavin"' ]

738
00:42:43,980 --> 00:42:45,673
Stop it.
Stop it.

739
00:42:45,746 --> 00:42:48,474
- I'm not in the mood!
- What do you mean
you're not in the mood?

740
00:42:48,546 --> 00:42:50,739
Honey, you better get in the mood,
'cause he's payin' the rent.

741
00:42:50,813 --> 00:42:54,643
Shut up, Venus!
Just what I said: I'm not in the mood.

742
00:42:54,713 --> 00:42:59,305
- Do I have to be in the mood
every time you are?
- Stop puttin' on the airs.

743
00:42:59,347 --> 00:43:02,642
- I'm not puttin' on airs.
- I never knew you when you wasn't
ready for a little action.

744
00:43:02,680 --> 00:43:06,635
Well, today, I'm not ready for action.
I'm tired. Rehearsal is hard.

745
00:43:06,713 --> 00:43:09,770
- Get your motor goin'.
- No!

746
00:43:09,846 --> 00:43:12,971
- Hey, I brought you somethin'.
- What?

747
00:43:13,047 --> 00:43:16,275
- Huh?
- Hmm.

748
00:43:16,347 --> 00:43:18,313
What do ya say?
Come on.

749
00:43:18,347 --> 00:43:21,404
- Nickie.
- Oh, I got a great bottle
of French wine.

750
00:43:21,480 --> 00:43:23,446
Joey Foster
made it himself.

751
00:43:23,513 --> 00:43:25,979
Pasadena. I'm pooped.

752
00:43:26,013 --> 00:43:28,377
Let's misbehave

753
00:43:28,447 --> 00:43:31,606
There's something wild
about you, child--

754
00:43:31,646 --> 00:43:34,010
[ David ] Today, Ellen came
to watch rehearsal.

755
00:43:34,080 --> 00:43:37,739
She was very excited to meet the cast,
especially Warner Purcell.

756
00:43:37,813 --> 00:43:42,541
- Warner, Warner, Warner.
This is Ellen. My girlfriend.
- Oh! Pleased to meet you.

757
00:43:42,613 --> 00:43:46,410
- You should be very proud.
He has a rare talent.
- Yes, he does.

758
00:43:46,480 --> 00:43:49,344
[ David ] The morning proceeded
very smoothly for the first half hour.

759
00:43:49,380 --> 00:43:51,346
And then
another incident occurred.

760
00:43:51,414 --> 00:43:55,437
The heart obeys
its own rules. Ha!

761
00:43:55,513 --> 00:43:59,969
As a doctor, your respect for
rationalities is not very profound.

762
00:44:00,047 --> 00:44:01,979
- David, I-- David, can I--
- [ David ] Yes?

763
00:44:02,047 --> 00:44:05,809
I don't understand the character here.
Suddenly, she's too wise.

764
00:44:05,880 --> 00:44:10,040
And, David, I don't know why she's
telling her to dump her fiance.

765
00:44:10,280 --> 00:44:12,643
- She's caught up with the Lieutenant.
- The Lieutenant?

766
00:44:12,680 --> 00:44:15,408
But it's as if she's just mouthing
the playwright's philosophy.

767
00:44:15,480 --> 00:44:18,673
- Why would she just up and leave Tom?
- Because she's impulsive.

768
00:44:18,713 --> 00:44:22,271
- It doesn't feel right.
- Well, yeah, and I don't
understand, you know...

769
00:44:22,347 --> 00:44:25,642
if I'm a doctor, how come
I'm giving her such bad advice?

770
00:44:25,680 --> 00:44:27,805
- It's not bad advice.
- It is bad advice.

771
00:44:27,880 --> 00:44:31,835
But, David, you see, in Act I,
she says that Tom changed her life.

772
00:44:31,913 --> 00:44:35,471
- Yes, but she's recklessly
driven to the Lieutenant.
- It doesn't make sense.

773
00:44:35,546 --> 00:44:37,842
- Just give it a chance.
- There's something
contradictory about it.

774
00:44:37,913 --> 00:44:40,277
- Just give it a chance.
- It's just bad writing.

775
00:44:40,347 --> 00:44:42,972
[ Cheech ]
I'll tell ya what's wrong.

776
00:44:43,047 --> 00:44:45,706
- Oh, Christ! Julian?
- Now let's wait a minute.

777
00:44:45,780 --> 00:44:49,610
- Let's not get into a situation here.
- She shouldn't leave the guy.

778
00:44:49,680 --> 00:44:51,805
She should stick with him.

779
00:44:51,880 --> 00:44:56,006
Then when the Lieutenant has
that fight with his wife and
walks out, he should notice her.

780
00:44:56,080 --> 00:44:58,739
That way,
it won't be boring.

781
00:45:07,013 --> 00:45:10,446
Somebody say something!

782
00:45:10,480 --> 00:45:13,968
- I think it's a good idea.
- [ Julian ] It's not a bad one.

783
00:45:14,047 --> 00:45:16,275
- You're kidding.
- Oh, no.

784
00:45:16,347 --> 00:45:18,505
It's, uh--
It really isn't.

785
00:45:18,579 --> 00:45:21,545
[ Warner ] Personally, I like it.
I think it's very dramatic.

786
00:45:21,613 --> 00:45:24,602
Ellen, do you see what I'm up against?
Do you see what I have to put up with?

787
00:45:24,680 --> 00:45:27,578
- I think he has an interesting concept.
- What?

788
00:45:27,646 --> 00:45:29,839
Not to say that--

789
00:45:29,913 --> 00:45:32,402
- She doesn't leave the Lieutenant.
- Right.

790
00:45:32,480 --> 00:45:34,502
- She doesn't leave her fiance.
- Right.

791
00:45:34,579 --> 00:45:37,875
We lose that scene, and suddenly
a lot of good possibilities open up.

792
00:45:37,946 --> 00:45:40,810
- [ Cheech ] It's a helluva lot
better than what you got.
- I actually like it.

793
00:45:40,880 --> 00:45:43,369
- You're taking his side?
- It's not a question of sides.

794
00:45:43,447 --> 00:45:46,810
- David, she's right.
The play always bogged down there.
- Try it.

795
00:45:46,846 --> 00:45:50,801
- That's why the actors
always looked so uncomfortable.
- I can't make those changes.

796
00:45:50,846 --> 00:45:55,279
- Why not? H-H-How do they meet again?
- Because the--

797
00:45:55,347 --> 00:45:59,676
The Lieutenant notices her, right?
And then, he goes after her.

798
00:45:59,713 --> 00:46:03,668
I mean, that's the way
it would happen in real life.
He goes after her. Come on.

799
00:46:03,746 --> 00:46:07,940
You can't force it, kid. I mean, if it's
meant to go in a whole other direction--

800
00:46:08,013 --> 00:46:11,468
- I quit!
- Oh, don't be so egotistical.

801
00:46:11,546 --> 00:46:13,705
- I'm outta here.
- Egotistical? Why?
Because I protect my play?

802
00:46:13,780 --> 00:46:17,304
- Protect it against what? A good idea?
- Oh, thank you for the support.

803
00:46:17,347 --> 00:46:20,540
- No, no, I quit! That's it. Good-bye.
- I'm gonna go shoot crap.

804
00:46:20,613 --> 00:46:22,806
- That's it. I quit.
- Wait a minute.

805
00:46:22,846 --> 00:46:25,812
[ Julian ]
David. David!

806
00:46:25,846 --> 00:46:28,039
- I'm gonna go shoot crap.
- David.

807
00:46:28,280 --> 00:46:31,474
- [ Mr. Woofles Barking ]
- Mommy's coming.

808
00:46:31,546 --> 00:46:36,501
If an artist can, it gives us all a
much better chance, and he is an artist.

809
00:46:36,546 --> 00:46:39,944
- Is that why he's getting all hot
and bothered all the time?
- Artists are very emotional.

810
00:46:40,013 --> 00:46:42,774
- Artists are emotional, are they?
- Yes, they are.

811
00:46:42,813 --> 00:46:45,608
Hey, I've been meaning
to ask ya...

812
00:46:45,680 --> 00:46:50,443
is it my imagination
or are you always... Iookin' my way?

813
00:46:50,513 --> 00:46:53,480
- You're a very observant girl.
Yes, I have been looking at you.
- Thank you.

814
00:46:53,513 --> 00:46:56,502
Yeah, well, I notice somethin'.
I notice you have...

815
00:46:56,546 --> 00:46:59,808
a really
big appetite.

816
00:46:59,880 --> 00:47:03,313
- Yes, I do have a big appetite.
- Yeah, I noticed that, but--

817
00:47:03,380 --> 00:47:05,437
- Where's your baby-sitter?
- What, Cheech?

818
00:47:05,513 --> 00:47:08,480
- Yes.
- Ah, you don't have to worry
about Cheech. He took off.

819
00:47:08,546 --> 00:47:12,569
- Did he?
- A minute there's a chance,
he runs off to play craps.

820
00:47:12,646 --> 00:47:16,044
- Takes about two hours.
- Well, listen, now that
you've been let off the leash...

821
00:47:16,280 --> 00:47:18,745
- Yeah?
- why don't we go in...

822
00:47:18,813 --> 00:47:22,075
- and get to know each other
a bit better?
- Okay.

823
00:47:22,314 --> 00:47:24,836
That might be pleasant.
[ Giggles ]

824
00:47:29,846 --> 00:47:31,505
- [ Giggles ]
- Well.

825
00:47:31,579 --> 00:47:33,511
- Hi.
- Hi.

826
00:47:33,579 --> 00:47:35,772
Hi.

827
00:47:38,480 --> 00:47:41,037
- You're a very attr--
Wait just a minute.
- What? What? What?

828
00:47:42,646 --> 00:47:44,908
- Before we start--
- Yeah?

829
00:47:44,980 --> 00:47:47,276
- What? Oh.
- Just a--

830
00:47:47,347 --> 00:47:50,370
A little poultry.
[ Giggles ]
Okay.

831
00:47:50,447 --> 00:47:52,379
- All right. Let's go.
- All right.

832
00:47:52,447 --> 00:47:54,935
You do have a big appetite.
[ Giggles ]

833
00:47:55,013 --> 00:47:58,468
- Pull yourself together.
So he came up with a good idea.
- [ Sighs ]

834
00:47:58,513 --> 00:48:00,945
- Helen, not you too?
- If you did follow his suggestion...

835
00:48:01,013 --> 00:48:04,275
you'd be able to put in that new scene
in Act Ill that you've always wanted to.

836
00:48:04,347 --> 00:48:08,279
- Yes, but it'd--
- And that, that casts
a whole new light...

837
00:48:08,347 --> 00:48:10,744
on my relationship
with my husband. Yes!

838
00:48:10,813 --> 00:48:13,439
So you're saying
you want me to change it?

839
00:48:13,513 --> 00:48:16,911
At the risk of seeing you
upset on your birthday.

840
00:48:16,980 --> 00:48:19,639
- How did you know it was my birthday?
- Happy birthday.

841
00:48:19,713 --> 00:48:22,907
- Helen! Ohh.
- Open it.

842
00:48:22,980 --> 00:48:25,571
Gosh!

843
00:48:25,646 --> 00:48:28,942
Oh, gosh.
Really. It's--

844
00:48:29,013 --> 00:48:31,740
Don't get too excited.
I didn't buy it.

845
00:48:31,813 --> 00:48:34,779
Cole Porter gave it to me.
It's one of many.

846
00:48:34,846 --> 00:48:37,438
- Now I'm gonna have to take up smoking.
- Hmm.

847
00:48:37,513 --> 00:48:40,570
Have a good time tonight
with your girlfriend.
I'm sure she's taking you out.

848
00:48:40,646 --> 00:48:44,738
- Yes, with the Marxes.
- Yes, well... make a birthday wish.

849
00:48:44,813 --> 00:48:49,609
- I have.
- I hope you get everything
in life that you want.

850
00:48:49,680 --> 00:48:51,612
Helen, have you thought
about what I said before...

851
00:48:51,646 --> 00:48:53,874
- about the way I feel?
- Don't speak.

852
00:48:55,080 --> 00:48:58,410
- But I want to express--
- Don't speak. Don't.

853
00:48:59,980 --> 00:49:01,912
- Just a few things I want to tell you.
- Don't speak.

854
00:49:01,980 --> 00:49:04,912
- When we first met-- [ Muffled ]
- No, no. Don't speak.

855
00:49:04,980 --> 00:49:08,037
Please don't speak.
Please don't speak.

856
00:49:08,280 --> 00:49:11,007
No! No!
No! Go!

857
00:49:11,080 --> 00:49:14,910
Go, gentle Scorpio, go!

858
00:49:14,980 --> 00:49:19,345
Your Pisces wishes you
every happy return.

859
00:49:20,047 --> 00:49:22,343
- Just one--
- Don't speak!

860
00:49:22,414 --> 00:49:24,641
##

861
00:49:24,713 --> 00:49:28,668
- [ Sighs ]
- Wow, a wallet!

862
00:49:28,713 --> 00:49:31,702
- That's appropriate.
- It was the nicest one I saw by far.

863
00:49:31,780 --> 00:49:35,042
- The piping. That's real leather.
- Places to put stuff in there.

864
00:49:35,280 --> 00:49:37,075
- You like it?
- It's amazing. Beautiful.

865
00:49:37,314 --> 00:49:39,303
- You like it?
- Yes, really.

866
00:49:39,347 --> 00:49:43,302
- Now all I need is some money,
and it'll hold its shape.
- You will prosper, my friend.

867
00:49:43,347 --> 00:49:46,540
- I promise. [ Chuckles ]
Am I right, Hilda?
- No, I love it.

868
00:49:46,613 --> 00:49:49,977
- Can I pick 'em or can I pick 'em?
- Oh, you sure can, Julian.

869
00:49:50,047 --> 00:49:53,036
- Happy birthday.
- Thank you. Thank you.
Thanks for spending it with me.

870
00:49:53,280 --> 00:49:55,609
- Oh, it's wonderful.
- Hilda, touch glasses there.

871
00:49:59,047 --> 00:50:02,604
Hey, look who's here
with his girlfriend.

872
00:50:02,680 --> 00:50:05,942
- [ Ellen ] Oh, no.
- I owe that big Gorgonzola an apology.

873
00:50:06,013 --> 00:50:10,604
What are you talking about?
Now that he's drunk, he's gonna
apologize to everyone. Strangers.

874
00:50:10,646 --> 00:50:14,908
[ David ] Today at rehearsal,
he came up with that little
suggestion, and I overreacted.

875
00:50:14,980 --> 00:50:18,776
I let my ego get in the way of the work,
and I feel I owe him an apology.

876
00:50:18,846 --> 00:50:22,370
- Ah, you're all right.
You handled it very well.
- I'll be right back.

877
00:50:30,380 --> 00:50:33,607
I take it all back. It was a good
suggestion, and I apologize.

878
00:50:33,680 --> 00:50:35,669
- Say hello to Violet.
- Hi, Violet.

879
00:50:35,746 --> 00:50:38,406
- Hi, nice to meet you.
Who's this, Cheech?
- He's a writer.

880
00:50:38,480 --> 00:50:42,344
- I'm a struggling writer.
- You wanna know what the problem
with your story is?

881
00:50:42,414 --> 00:50:46,471
- What's the problem?
Are you gonna do some more rewrites?
- Sit down. Take a load off your feet.

882
00:50:46,513 --> 00:50:50,276
- Moe, go on. Come here. Get him a beer.
- Why not?

883
00:50:50,314 --> 00:50:52,303
- [ Violet ] He's a writer?
- Yeah.

884
00:50:52,347 --> 00:50:55,642
- I didn't know you knew writers.
- Do me a favor. Shut up.

885
00:50:55,713 --> 00:50:57,645
Don't tell me
to shut up.

886
00:50:57,680 --> 00:51:00,044
All right,
number one.

887
00:51:00,280 --> 00:51:03,405
See, I don't believe she loves
the guy right from the start.

888
00:51:03,480 --> 00:51:06,934
She's too on, uh, top of him
all the time. That's not love.

889
00:51:07,013 --> 00:51:10,809
That's like keeping somebody in prison.
But if you changed it, right?

890
00:51:10,880 --> 00:51:13,675
And she left him,
then she would feel so bad about it...

891
00:51:13,746 --> 00:51:17,610
- that she would have the
nervous breakdown and go nuts.
- [ Music Stops, Applause ]

892
00:51:17,680 --> 00:51:20,442
- How ya doin', Cheech?
- Tulio, listen, I gotta see you later.

893
00:51:20,513 --> 00:51:23,968
- I wanna get down on the Cardinals
for the doubleheader, all right?
- You got it.

894
00:51:24,047 --> 00:51:28,309
- Them birds look good.
- Teach your friend some manners
and get him outta here.

895
00:51:28,347 --> 00:51:30,835
- All right, so--
- You were-- You were talking about--

896
00:51:30,913 --> 00:51:33,504
Right, all right.
So, now...

897
00:51:33,579 --> 00:51:37,636
if the doctor feels what Sylvia's
feelin'-- That's her name, Sylvia.

898
00:51:37,713 --> 00:51:40,043
- There's a Sylvia in my neighborhood.
- Oh, yeah?

899
00:51:40,280 --> 00:51:43,541
-Yeah. What was her name? Sylvia Pincus.
-Sylvia Pincus.

900
00:51:43,613 --> 00:51:46,375
Sylvia Pincus. Big, fat Jewish broad,
had a little tiny husband.

901
00:51:46,447 --> 00:51:49,277
She chopped him up with an ax and mailed
his pieces all over the country.

902
00:51:49,347 --> 00:51:51,676
I don't know what
she was tryin' to prove.

903
00:51:51,746 --> 00:51:53,678
That's disgusting. You gotta
tell that story in front of me?

904
00:51:53,746 --> 00:51:55,372
- Relax.
- You know I got a weak stomach.

905
00:51:55,447 --> 00:51:57,912
- You were tellin' me
about the play a minute ago.
- Don't interrupt me.

906
00:51:57,980 --> 00:52:00,912
- You were sayin' about Sylvia?
- Right. So if the doctor feels
what Sylvia's feelin'--

907
00:52:00,980 --> 00:52:02,969
- Uh-huh.
- Know what I mean?

908
00:52:03,047 --> 00:52:06,013
Yeah. She identifies
with her patient, a bit.

909
00:52:06,047 --> 00:52:09,843
Right. This way when she gets jealous,
it makes sense.

910
00:52:09,880 --> 00:52:11,812
- Right.
- Uh-huh.

911
00:52:11,880 --> 00:52:14,675
There's gotta be a time when the
Lieutenant has it out with the doctor.

912
00:52:14,746 --> 00:52:16,678
Why isn't that in there?

913
00:52:16,746 --> 00:52:18,871
You're talking about a whole
different direction for the play.

914
00:52:18,946 --> 00:52:20,878
Definitely.

915
00:52:22,613 --> 00:52:24,545
Think about it.

916
00:52:24,613 --> 00:52:28,376
How would the audience know
Sylvia was feeling guilty? lf--

917
00:52:28,447 --> 00:52:30,605
Oh. I don't know.

918
00:52:30,680 --> 00:52:32,646
Wait a minute.
Yeah. Wait.

919
00:52:32,680 --> 00:52:36,635
You could work it out with maybe you--
you hear what she's thinkin'.

920
00:52:36,680 --> 00:52:39,612
-You mean she speaks her thoughts aloud?
-Sure, why not? It's a play anyhow.

921
00:52:39,680 --> 00:52:42,771
It don't have to be real,
but it'll be stronger.

922
00:52:42,813 --> 00:52:46,609
You think about that.
And you, don't interrupt me no more.

923
00:52:46,680 --> 00:52:48,612
I'm sorry.

924
00:52:50,380 --> 00:52:54,971
So how come you had so much
to say to that Valenti goon?

925
00:52:55,047 --> 00:52:57,512
No, nothing. I was just
thanking him for his ideas.

926
00:52:57,546 --> 00:53:01,603
- What ideas? He only had
the one suggestion, didn't he?
- Yeah.

927
00:53:01,680 --> 00:53:04,646
- That was just it.
- So do you like your wallet?

928
00:53:04,680 --> 00:53:06,646
- What?
- The wallet.

929
00:53:06,680 --> 00:53:08,976
- Oh, yes, yes, it's terrific.
- Are you sure?

930
00:53:09,013 --> 00:53:12,536
Oh, it's very exciting. I love
leatherette. Always have loved it.

931
00:53:12,613 --> 00:53:14,943
Boy, are you loaded.

932
00:53:15,013 --> 00:53:17,002
- Yeah.
- Happy birthday.

933
00:53:17,080 --> 00:53:19,012
Thanks.

934
00:53:21,347 --> 00:53:26,279
[ David ] September 24. I gave the cast
the rewrites. Everyone seemed pleased.

935
00:53:26,347 --> 00:53:29,040
- [ Helen ] These are brilliant! Oh!
- [ Warner ] They are.

936
00:53:29,280 --> 00:53:31,269
Now Sylvia's
not so passive.

937
00:53:31,347 --> 00:53:35,302
She uses her wiles to trap
the Lieutenant, and that's
what causes her guilt!

938
00:53:35,380 --> 00:53:37,811
[ Warner ] The whole thing is motivated.
It drives on. Wonderful.

939
00:53:37,880 --> 00:53:41,404
- [ Olive ] You mean I gotta
memorize all new lines?
- [ Helen ] They're wonderful!

940
00:53:41,480 --> 00:53:45,707
- How did you come up
with such divine changes?
- They're not really mine--

941
00:53:45,780 --> 00:53:49,712
- Oh, no? Whose are they, God's?
- [ Laughing ]

942
00:53:49,780 --> 00:53:53,507
- Well, they are mine
in the sense that they're mine--
- Your modesty becomes you.

943
00:53:53,579 --> 00:53:55,738
But let's face it;
you are a major talent.

944
00:53:55,813 --> 00:53:57,870
A major new voice
in the theater.

945
00:53:57,946 --> 00:54:01,470
The word genius gets thrown around
so frequently in this business...

946
00:54:01,513 --> 00:54:03,945
- but, darling, if the shoe fits--
- Congratulations.

947
00:54:04,013 --> 00:54:07,945
- It finally has balls.
- Now, if we can do something
about Act Ill...

948
00:54:08,013 --> 00:54:10,411
we got a big, fat hit
on our hands.

949
00:54:10,480 --> 00:54:14,310
- [ Warner ] Three cheers
for the writer! Hip-hip--
- [ Cast ] Hooray!

950
00:54:14,347 --> 00:54:17,540
[ David ] I stayed up all night
working on the third act.

951
00:54:17,613 --> 00:54:19,545
I admit it came rather hard...

952
00:54:19,613 --> 00:54:22,841
and before I handed in the pages,
I sent them over to Cheech to read.

953
00:54:22,913 --> 00:54:25,640
He suggested I come down
to his office.

954
00:54:29,780 --> 00:54:32,372
- You missed the idea.
- I did?

955
00:54:32,447 --> 00:54:35,004
Yeah, you did.
Plus, nobody talks like that.

956
00:54:35,080 --> 00:54:38,512
- You got that problem.
You don't write like people talk.
- I take poetic license.

957
00:54:38,579 --> 00:54:43,274
Poetic license, bullshit.
People believe what they see
when the actors sound real.

958
00:54:43,347 --> 00:54:46,313
- Come here. Let me show you.
- What are you doing?

959
00:54:46,380 --> 00:54:48,369
- What does it look like I'm doin'?
- You're gonna write it?

960
00:54:48,447 --> 00:54:52,640
What am l? A fuckin' idiot?
They taught me how to write in
school before I burned it down.

961
00:54:52,680 --> 00:54:56,806
- You burned down your school?
- Yeah, it was Lincoln's birthday.
There was nobody there.

962
00:54:56,880 --> 00:54:59,903
- If you actually write--
- Look, I know how people talk,
all right?

963
00:54:59,980 --> 00:55:01,946
Go shoot a rack,
and let me do this.

964
00:55:01,980 --> 00:55:04,775
But if you actually write it,
then I'm not--

965
00:55:04,846 --> 00:55:07,335
- Don't worry about it.
I ain't gonna tell anybody.
- No?

966
00:55:07,414 --> 00:55:10,346
No. I saw you playin' the big shot.
I know what it's all about.

967
00:55:10,414 --> 00:55:12,811
Where I come from,
nobody squeals.

968
00:55:18,513 --> 00:55:20,672
Go shoot a rack.

969
00:55:20,746 --> 00:55:23,076
Stop starin' at me.

970
00:55:23,314 --> 00:55:27,269
[ Helen ] What dialogue!
This is better than O'Neill!

971
00:55:27,347 --> 00:55:28,835
Max Anderson
will never touch you!

972
00:55:28,913 --> 00:55:30,845
So you liked it.

973
00:55:30,913 --> 00:55:34,709
It's so full of passion!
It's so full of life!

974
00:55:34,780 --> 00:55:38,769
- I hoped it would lift the story.
- What a difference between this
and your first draft.

975
00:55:38,846 --> 00:55:43,801
You hadn't found yourself yet. The idea
was there, but it hadn't crystallized.

976
00:55:43,880 --> 00:55:46,675
You needed to hear it
on its feet, and now this.

977
00:55:46,746 --> 00:55:49,769
It's no longer tepid
and cerebral.

978
00:55:49,813 --> 00:55:53,643
It's full of life!
It's full of passion!

979
00:55:53,713 --> 00:55:57,736
It reeks with humid sexuality!
It's carnivorous at last!

980
00:55:57,813 --> 00:56:02,337
- You thought my first draft
was cerebral and tepid?
- Only the plot and dialogue.

981
00:56:02,414 --> 00:56:06,437
- But this--
- Was-Was-Was there nothing
in the original draft...

982
00:56:06,513 --> 00:56:08,480
that you feel
is worth saving?

983
00:56:08,513 --> 00:56:11,775
The stage directions were lucid.
Best I've ever seen.

984
00:56:11,813 --> 00:56:14,506
- And the color of the binder.
Good choice.
- Thank you.

985
00:56:14,579 --> 00:56:16,636
I always had a flare
for stage directions.

986
00:56:16,713 --> 00:56:20,941
I went back and reread your
earlier plays. They suffered
from the same problem.

987
00:56:20,980 --> 00:56:24,673
- [ Sighs ]
- Good ideas, but
too contrived, no real guts.

988
00:56:24,746 --> 00:56:26,735
It's like you
finally happened.

989
00:56:26,813 --> 00:56:29,075
- Helen, I have a confession to make.
- Yes?

990
00:56:29,314 --> 00:56:31,643
[ Inhales Deeply ]

991
00:56:31,713 --> 00:56:34,009
- I--
- Don't speak!

992
00:56:34,080 --> 00:56:36,807
No, no, don't speak.
I know you wanna deprecate yourself.

993
00:56:36,880 --> 00:56:41,279
I know you do, but you're
going to take this town by storm.

994
00:56:45,513 --> 00:56:47,638
I didn't...

995
00:56:48,913 --> 00:56:51,606
realize what
an inspiration...

996
00:56:51,646 --> 00:56:53,942
you've been
to my writing.

997
00:56:54,013 --> 00:56:56,501
Oh, David.

998
00:56:56,546 --> 00:56:58,842
Dear, dear David.

999
00:56:58,913 --> 00:57:01,936
Pungent,
seething artist.

1000
00:57:01,980 --> 00:57:04,810
The cocoon
has opened.

1001
00:57:09,713 --> 00:57:13,509
I would give my body freely to
the man who wrote those words.

1002
00:57:13,579 --> 00:57:17,602
Those glorious,
powerful words.

1003
00:57:17,680 --> 00:57:19,612
- Helen--
- No, don't speak.

1004
00:57:19,680 --> 00:57:22,976
- [ Mumbling ]
- Don't speak. Don't speak.
No. Silence. Silence.

1005
00:57:23,047 --> 00:57:25,911
- Don't speak.
- [ Mumbles ] Please.

1006
00:57:29,280 --> 00:57:32,734
[ David ] September 28.
The play is working much better now.

1007
00:57:32,813 --> 00:57:36,745
Helen has been getting on more
pleasantly with Eden, and I
believe she likes Mr. Woofles.

1008
00:57:36,813 --> 00:57:40,439
- [ Barking ]
- Back! Back! Back! Back!

1009
00:57:40,480 --> 00:57:44,310
[ David ] Warner Purcell and Olive seem
to always be exchanging coy glances.

1010
00:57:44,347 --> 00:57:47,801
I don't know if it's my imagination, but
he seems to have put on a little weight.

1011
00:57:47,880 --> 00:57:53,676
Perhaps the tension of our
upcoming Boston opening has
caused him to cheat on his diet.

1012
00:57:53,746 --> 00:57:55,939
[ David ] Can we go
from "God of our fathers"?

1013
00:57:59,480 --> 00:58:01,809
Take it from
"God of our fathers."

1014
00:58:07,780 --> 00:58:13,077
[ Ellen ] Oh! God of our fathers,
help me! Help me!

1015
00:58:13,314 --> 00:58:17,406
I was thinkin' about
when Sylvia's in the crazy house--

1016
00:58:17,480 --> 00:58:19,412
- Sanitarium.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

1017
00:58:19,480 --> 00:58:22,310
- She gets the D.T.s,
and she sees things.
- She hallucinates.

1018
00:58:22,347 --> 00:58:26,006
- No, she sees things.
You know, like visions.
- Like what kind of visions?

1019
00:58:26,080 --> 00:58:30,410
- Like her dead husband,
and then they have that talk.
- The one in the third act?

1020
00:58:30,480 --> 00:58:33,843
That's right. She couldn't
face up to him when he was alive.

1021
00:58:33,913 --> 00:58:37,437
That's great. That's great.
That's great.

1022
00:58:37,513 --> 00:58:39,843
- It is great.
- Why didn't I think of that?

1023
00:58:40,913 --> 00:58:42,879
Joe,
gimme a beer.

1024
00:58:50,746 --> 00:58:53,769
That's great.
It's all great.

1025
00:58:53,846 --> 00:58:55,812
What's the matter?

1026
00:58:55,846 --> 00:58:58,005
Nothin'. I just gotta
take a break for a minute.

1027
00:58:58,080 --> 00:59:00,410
- You wanna take a break?
- Yeah.

1028
00:59:00,480 --> 00:59:04,412
- All right.
- Got a cramp.

1029
00:59:04,480 --> 00:59:06,469
[ Billiard Balls Clacking ]

1030
00:59:07,579 --> 00:59:09,772
Man.

1031
00:59:09,813 --> 00:59:13,007
[ Sighs ]
It's a nice-- nice spot.

1032
00:59:13,080 --> 00:59:15,012
- Come here a long time.
- Yeah?

1033
00:59:15,080 --> 00:59:17,739
- Yeah.
- You from around here?
You live around here?

1034
00:59:17,813 --> 00:59:21,041
- New York, born and raised.
West 45th Street.
- Mmm.

1035
00:59:23,846 --> 00:59:26,641
- Got a big family?
- No.

1036
00:59:26,713 --> 00:59:29,407
Got a sister who
lives in Jersey.

1037
00:59:29,480 --> 00:59:32,378
I had a brother,
but he got killed.

1038
00:59:32,447 --> 00:59:35,503
- I'm sorry.
- It's all right.

